{The symmetrical pawn structure #2 is more typical for the Exchange Slav with
3.cxd5 cxd5. Black's g7 bishop is biting on the e3, d4 wall and the weakening
of the dark squares on the queenside (c5, c7, d6) automaticaly makes the
situation far more pleasant for White The control over the only open file is
of primary importance. It is usually White who manage this while Black
urgently needs to redirect the dark-squared bishop back to the f8-a3 diagonal.
The endgames are in White's favor as well because there is nothing Black can
do against the increasing queenside pressure.}  *

