{This game is a model for what White should aim for. The plan of taking
control over the c-file is easy and straighforward, while Black is short of
any positive defensive ideas.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qb3 g6 5. Nc3
Bg7 6. cxd5 cxd5 7. Bg5 e6 8. e3 O-O 9. h3 b6 (9... Nc6 10. Bd3 Na5 {
Tkachiev-Berend Nancy 2005}) 10. Bd3 Bb7 11. O-O Nc6 12. Rfc1 ({The immediate} 
12. Ne5 {is good as well} h6 {Ree-Malich Budapest 1978} 13. Nxc6 $1 (13. Bh4 g5
14. Bg3 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Ne4 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Rfc1 $1 $14) 13... Bxc6 14. Bf4 $14
) 12... Qe7 (12... Qd7 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Ne4 15. Bb5 $18) (12... Na5 13.
Qd1 $14) 13. Ne5 $1 {The battle for the c-file begins.} Rfc8 14. Nxc6 $1 (14.
Ng4 h5 15. Ne5 Qf8) (14. f4 h6 15. Bh4 Qf8) 14... Rxc6 (14... Bxc6 15. Rc2 Qb7
16. Rac1 $14 {is the same}) 15. Rc2 h6 ({Unfortunately,} 15... Rac8 $2 {
is just impossible} 16. Bb5 R6c7 17. Bf4 {[%csl Rc7]}) 16. Bf4 Rcc8 (16... Ne4
17. Nxe4 Rxc2 18. Qxc2 dxe4 19. Bxe4 Rc8 20. Qd3 Bxe4 21. Qxe4) 17. Rac1 Ne8
18. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gc1c8] Black needs good advice as he is losing
control over the c-file and the g7-bishop is just a mere spectator.} Rxc2 ({
From this moment onward} 18... a6 {was never possible because of} 19. Nc7 $18)
19. Rxc2 Bf8 20. Rc3 $1 h5 21. a3 Qd8 22. Qc2 Ba6 (22... Nd6 23. Nxd6 Bxd6 24.
Bxd6 Qxd6 25. Rc7 Rb8 26. Rxb7 Rxb7 27. Qc8+) (22... Kh7 23. Bxg6+ fxg6 24. Nc7
) 23. Qa4 $1 {getting the bishop pair.} Bxb5 (23... Bb7 24. Nc7 $18) 24. Bxb5
Nd6 25. Bc6 (25. Ba6 b5 26. Bxb5 $18) 25... Rc8 26. Qxa7 {Winning a pawn.
Black's counterplay is insufficient.} Ne4 27. Rc2 g5 28. Be5 f6 (28... Bd6 29.
Bxd6 Nxd6 30. Ba4 $18) 29. Bh2 g4 30. hxg4 hxg4 31. Bf4 Bd6 32. Bxd6 Qxd6 33.
Ba4 Rxc2 34. Bxc2 Ng5 35. Qb7 f5 36. Ba4 g3 37. f4 Ne4 38. Qc8+ Kg7 39. Bd7 Qe7
40. Bxe6 Nf6 41. b4 b5 42. Kh1 Ng4 43. Qd7 Qxd7 44. Bxd7 Nxe3 45. Bxb5 Kf6 46.
a4 Ke7 47. a5 Kd8 48. Ba4 Kc7 49. Kg1 Kc8 50. Bc6 Kb8 51. b5 Kc7 52. Be8 Nc4
53. Bf7 Ne3 54. Be6 Kd6 55. b6 Kc6 56. Bc8 Nc2 57. b7 Kc7 58. a6 Kb8 59. Bxf5
Nb4 60. Be6 *

