[PlyCount "0"]
[EventDate "2019.04.16"]

{The pawn structure #4 is typical for the line 4...dxc4 5.Qxc4 Bg4 6.Nc3 Nbd7
7.e4 Bxf3 8.gxf3 e5. Usually in this structure, the kings get castled to
opposite sides which considerably sharpens the fight. White's spoiled pawn
structure is compensated by the bishop pair in a position with an open center.
Black should carefuly handle the blockade on the dark squares as otherwise
White could achieve the advances f4 followed by e5 which would put Black in a
dire situation. You can see from the test positions that a slight inaccuracy
might be deadly punished. In positions with opposite castles, the open g-file
offers White much better chances to deliver mate. A typical manouevre is
Ne2-g3-f5. The positions are usually very tactical where every tempo matters.} 
*

