{[%evp 0,27,30,30,20,-9,32,31,49,6,41,35,34,-1,53,43,88,39,48,36,29,10,35,-5,
39,27,31,51,48,52]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 a6 {[%emt 0:00:05]
Black is ready to play a Chebanenko Slav, and with e3 White can directly
transpose to this line. But if White is looking to achieve an advantage, he
should opt for a line where a6 will be less useful. In my opinion, if White
wishes to continue in the spirit of 4.Qc2, he should either play 5.Bf4 or 5.g3.
} 5. Bf4 $1 (5. Nbd2 $5 {should give White a small advantage.} g6 (5... e6 6.
g3 Be7 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O $14) 6. e3 Bg7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O Nbd7 (8... Bg4 9. h3
Bxf3 10. Nxf3 $14) 9. b3 (9. cxd5 cxd5 10. b3 Nb8 11. Ba3 $14 {
Topalov-Gashimov Linares 2010}) 9... c5 10. Bb2 b6 11. Rfd1 Bb7 12. dxc5 Nxc5
13. Be2 Rc8 14. Rac1 e6 15. Bd4 $14) (5. g3 {White continues in Catalan style,
hoping that a6 will be less useful. If Black plays 5...dc4 or 5...g6, White
can keep the pressure, but in case of 5...Bg4 he has nothing special.} Bg4 $1 (
5... g6 6. Bg2 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. Rd1 $14) (5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qc2 Bb7 8.
Bg2 Nbd7 9. O-O e6 10. Ne5 $1 {, and White took over the initiative in the
games Wang, Y-Wheeler, C chess.com INT 2019 and Savchenko, B -Geller, J
Voronezh 2007.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd5 (11... Nd7 12. Rd1 Qc7 13. a4 b4 14. Nd2 Nxe5
15. Ne4 c5 16. Bf4 Bd5 17. a5 Rc8 18. Rxd5 $1 exd5 19. Rd1 $40) 12. Nc3 Be7 13.
Rd1 $36) 6. Bg2 (6. Ne5 Bh5 7. Bg2 (7. Qb3 b5 $5 {This is the main idea behind
a6 - to prepare Bg4 and to meet Qb3 with b5.} (7... Ra7 $5 $11) 8. c5 a5 9. Bg2
e6 $11) 7... e6 8. O-O Be7 9. Bf4 O-O 10. Re1 Nbd7 $11) 6... e6 7. O-O Nbd7 8.
Nbd2 Bf5 $1 (8... Be7 9. e4 O-O $11) 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. c5 Qxb3 11. axb3 h6 $1 12.
b4 (12. h4 Be7 13. b4 Ne4 14. Nb3 g5 $1) 12... Be7 13. Nb3 g5 $1 {, taking the
f4- square under control.} 14. Na5 Rb8 15. h4 Ne4 $11) 5... dxc4 $1 (5... g6 6.
e3 $14) (5... Bg4 $6 6. Ne5 $1 Bh5 7. Qb3 $1 {Suddenly in the game Pelletier,
Y-Slobodjan,R France 2003, Black had great problems.} Ra7 $2 (7... b5 8. cxb5
$1 (8. cxd5 Qxd5 $13) 8... axb5 9. Qh3 Ra4 10. e3 $1 (10. g4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 fxg6
12. e3 e5 $1) 10... e6 11. Nc3 Bb4 12. g4 Bg6 13. Nxg6 fxg6 14. g5 Ne4 15.
Qxe6+ Qe7 16. Qc8+ Qd8 17. Qxd8+ Kxd8 18. Bxb8 Nxc3 19. Bd3 $16) 8. Qh3 $1 dxc4
9. Nc3 b5 10. g4 Bg6 11. Bg2 $40) (5... e6 6. e3 Nbd7 7. Nc3 Be7 8. h3 O-O 9.
Rd1 $1 {And we have another well-known position from the QGD, but with the
bishop on f4. Compared to the usual positions with the bishop on g5 White
might have the slightly better prospects.} (9. cxd5 $5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5 11.
Bd3 Bb4+ 12. Nd2 $14 {Van Wely,L -Vaganian,R Dordrecht 1999}) 9... dxc4 10.
Bxc4 b5 11. Bd3 (11. Be2 Bb7 12. Ne5 c5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. O-O Qe7) 11... Qb6 (
11... Bb7 $6 12. e4 $14) 12. Ne5 (12. e4 c5 13. e5 c4 $1 $132) 12... c5 {
Now in the game Cmilyte -Charchalis Kozsalin 1999 White won a pawn,} 13. Nxd7
Bxd7 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Bxh7+ Nxh7 16. Rxd7 {, but Black could have achieved
some compensation after} Rfc8 $1 (16... e5 17. Rd5 Qc6 18. Rxe5 Qxg2 19. Qe4
$16) 17. Qd1 Bf6 $44) 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qc2 {The other retreats are not sufficient
for an advantage.} (7. Qd3 Bb7 8. e4 e6 9. Nc3 c5 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8
12. Bd3 Nbd7 $11) (7. Qb3 e6 8. a4 Be7 9. e3 Bb7 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Nbd7 12.
Rd1 c5 13. axb5 axb5 14. Rxa8 Qxa8 15. Qxb5 $11 {Xiong,J -Motylev, A Tbilisi
2017}) 7... Bb7 8. g3 ({If you want to add some attacking spirit to your game,
you might like to try} 8. Nc3 $5 e6 (8... c5 9. dxc5) 9. Rd1 $1 (9. e4 c5 $1)
9... Nbd7 10. e4 b4 (10... c5 11. d5 $1 c4 (11... b4 $2 12. dxe6 fxe6 13. Qb3
$18) 12. dxe6 fxe6 13. Be2 Bb4 (13... Bc5 14. O-O O-O 15. e5 $18) 14. O-O Qe7
15. e5 Nd5 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Ng5 $40) 11. Na4 c5 12. d5 $1 exd5 13. exd5 Nxd5 (
13... Bxd5 14. Bd3 Be7 (14... Bxf3 15. gxf3 Be7 16. O-O O-O) 15. O-O Bxf3 16.
gxf3 O-O 17. Rfe1 $44) 14. Bg3 Be7 15. Bc4 N7f6 16. O-O O-O 17. Rd2 Qa5 18.
Rfd1 Rad8 19. Ne5 Rfe8 20. Bd3 $44) 8... Nbd7 9. Bg2 e6 (9... c5 10. dxc5 Qc8
11. O-O Qxc5 12. Qxc5 Nxc5 13. Rc1 e6 14. Nbd2 Be7 15. Rc2 O-O 16. Rac1 Rfc8
17. Ne5 $14) (9... Rc8 10. Ne5 Qb6 11. O-O e6 12. Rd1 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Nc3
Be7 15. Ne4 c5 16. Bg5 $36) 10. Ne5 $1 Nxe5 {Black should exchange the knights,
as otherwise his position is very dangerous.} (10... Nd5 11. O-O c5 12. dxc5
Nxc5 13. Rd1 Qb6 14. Bxd5 $1 Bxd5 15. Nc3 Bb7 16. b4 $18) 11. Bxe5 Rc8 12. O-O
Be7 13. Nd2 O-O 14. Rfd1 $14 {White enjoys much better chances, as is usual
when Black delays c6-c5 in the extended fianchetto systems. The c5-square is
weak and the b7-bishop is out of play.} *

