c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 Bg4 5. Ne5 $1 {This is White's only try for an advantage.
The modest} (5. Nbd2 e6 6. g3 Nbd7 7. Bg2 Be7 8. O-O O-O {leads to a position
where White doesn't have an active plan. For example} 9. e4 (9. b3 Bf5 10. Qd1
Ne4 11. Bb2 a5 12. a3 b5 $1 $132) (9. Re1 Bf5 10. Qb3 Qa5 $1 {Protecting b7 in
the most active way.} 11. Nh4 (11. Qxb7 $4 Rab8 12. Qxc6 Rfc8 $19) 11... Be4 $1
12. f3 $2 dxc4 $36) 9... Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Bf5 $1 $11) 5... e6 $1 {Black gives up
the bishop pair, but there was not much of a choice anyway.} (5... Be6 6. cxd5
$1 cxd5 {In this symmetrical pawn structure White enjoys the more pleasant
game - see the pawn structure section.} (6... Bxd5 $6 7. Nc3 Nbd7 8. e4 Be6 9.
h3 $1 Nxe5 (9... g6 10. Nf3 $16) 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. f4 g6 (11... Nb6 12. a4) 12.
f5 $1 $16) (6... Nxd5 7. Nf3 $1 Bg4 8. e4 $1 Bxf3 9. gxf3 {о x} Nb4 $2 10. Qb3
Qxd4 11. Be3 $18) 7. Qb3 $1 Qc8 (7... Nc6 8. Qxb7 Nxd4 9. Na3 $1 Nd7 10. e3 $16
) (7... Qb6 $6 8. Qxb6 axb6 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. e3 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Ne4 (11... Nd7 12.
Bb5 $14) 12. Nb5 $1 $14) 8. Bf4 Nc6 9. Nc3 $1 Nxd4 10. Qa4+ Nc6 11. e4 $1 dxe4
12. Bb5 Bd7 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 (13... bxc6 $2 14. Ba6) 14. Bxc6+ Qxc6 (14... bxc6
15. Rc1 Qb7 16. O-O $14) 15. Nb5 e5 16. Rc1 Bc5 17. Nc7+ Kd7 18. Qxc6+ bxc6 19.
Nxa8 exf4 20. Rxc5 Rxa8 21. Rc4 Rb8 22. b3 $14 {Although Black has two pawns
for the exchange, White should be better in this endgame.}) 6. Nxg4 (6. Qb3 $5
{I considered to choose this move as a mainline, but Black has a very strong
reply:} Nbd7 $1 {Again the most active way to protect the pawn.} (6... Qc7 7.
Nxg4 Nxg4 8. Nd2 Nd7 9. g3 Be7 10. Bg2 O-O 11. O-O) (6... Qb6 7. c5 Qxb3 8.
axb3 Nbd7 (8... Bf5 9. b4 (9. Bf4 Nbd7 10. b4) 9... Nbd7 10. Nf3 Be7 11. Nc3
O-O 12. h3 Ne4 13. Bf4 a6 14. e3) 9. Nxg4 Nxg4 10. b4 Be7 11. h3 Ngf6 12. Bf4
a6 13. e3 O-O 14. Nc3 $14) 7. Nxg4 (7. Qxb7 $6 Nxe5 8. dxe5 Nd7 $40) 7... Nxg4
8. Nd2 (8. Qxb7 $6 Rb8 9. Qxa7 Bb4+ 10. Nc3 O-O 11. h3 Ngf6 $36) 8... Rb8 9. e3
Bd6 $11) 6... Nxg4 7. e3 {This is a typical position from the Slav 4. e3 line
- Black gives up the bishop pair, relying on his good development and centre
control. It is not easy to make progress without further simplifications.} Nd7
(7... f5 {Setting up a Stonewall without the bad bishop is tempting, but not
sufficient for equality} 8. Nc3 Nf6 9. h3 Bd6 10. g4 g6 11. gxf5 gxf5 12. Rg1
Nbd7 13. Bd2 Kf7 14. O-O-O $40) 8. Be2 (8. Nd2 Qh4 9. g3 Qf6 $17) 8... Ngf6 (
8... Bb4+ 9. Nc3 $1 Qh4 10. g3 Qh3 11. Bf1 Qh5 12. h3 Ngf6 13. Be2 Qg6 14. Bd3
Qh5 15. Bd2 O-O 16. a3 Bd6 17. g4 Qh4 18. O-O-O $16) (8... f5 $6 9. cxd5 cxd5
10. e4 $1) 9. O-O Bd6 (9... Be7 10. b3 (10. Nc3 O-O 11. b3 Re8 12. Bb2 Bf8 13.
Rad1 $14 {Cserna,L -Chernin,A Copenhagen 1986}) 10... O-O 11. Bb2 Re8 12. Nd2
$14) (9... dxc4 10. Nd2 $1) 10. Nd2 O-O 11. c5 $1 {In my opinion this is
White's only way to fight for an advantage.} (11. b3 Qe7 12. Bb2 Ba3 $5) 11...
Bc7 12. f4 $1 {White's plan is to advance on the queenside with b4-b5, but it
is necessary to stop Black actions in the centre first.} (12. b4 e5 13. Bb2 Re8
14. Rfe1 $14 {is also better for White, but Black has some counterplay.}) 12...
a5 $1 {Otherwise White achieves b4, completing the bind.} 13. b3 (13. Nf3 Ne4)
13... Qe7 {Black is preparing b6.} (13... Qc8 14. g4 $1 b6 $2 (14... g6 15. Bb2
b6 16. cxb6 Bxb6 17. Rac1 $16) 15. g5 Ne8 16. cxb6 Bxb6 17. Ba3 $18) 14. Bb2 (
14. g4) (14. a3 b6) 14... Rfc8 (14... b6 $6 {White can just take the pawn:} 15.
cxb6 Bxb6 16. Qxc6 Rfc8 17. Qb5 Rc2 18. Bc1 $1 Ne4 (18... Rac8 19. Bd3) (18...
Rc3 19. Nb1) 19. Nxe4 dxe4 20. Bd1 $16) 15. g4 $1 {White starts the offensive
on the kingside, for example} ({The safer} 15. a3 b6 16. b4 axb4 17. axb4 bxc5
18. bxc5 $14 {guarantees White a stable advantage.}) 15... b6 16. g5 Ne8 17.
Rac1 $1 bxc5 18. dxc5 e5 19. Bg4 $1 Rcb8 20. Nf3 $40 {White's attack is
furious.} *

