{[%evp 0,33,30,30,20,-11,45,30,30,9,6,7,-10,-29,55,25,0,30,50,22,45,43,64,39,
59,58,36,17,11,44,44,42,13,13,106,57]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 g6 {
I think there is one important difference between the 4.Qc2 g6 system and the
Gruenfeld Defence, which is in White's favour: In the Gruenfeld Defence, Black
usually challenges the center with c7-c5, while in the 4.Qc2 g6 line, Black is
only holding it with c6 and d5. If Black is looking for active counterplay at
some point, he has to play c6-c5, which would lose a clear tempo compared to
the Gruenfeld lines. Another option to create counterplay is to chase White's
queen by means of Bf5 & Na6-b4.} 5. Bf4 {Now Black has a choice between three
main continuations: The more direct 2.1. - 5...dxc4, 2.2. - 5...Bf5 or 2.3 5...
Bg7 6 e3 0-0, completing development before starting actions in the centre.} ({
2.4} 5. cxd5 {We saw in Chapter 1, Line 1.1.2 that fixing the structure is the
safest path for White to avoid complications whilst achieving a small but
stable advantage in the arising symmetrical positions.}) 5... dxc4 $5 {This is
the usual choice of Gruenfeld experts such as Kasparov, Gelfand, Svidler and
Kamsky. Black is playing in the true spirit of the Gruenfeld Defense by giving
away the centre control while preparing strong counterplay by Be6, Nd5 and c5.}
(5... Bg7 6. e3 O-O 7. Nc3 c5 {A3}) (5... Bf5 6. Qb3 Qb6 {A2 ) are the two
other main attempts for Black.}) (5... Na6 $5 6. e3 Bf5 7. Qb3 Nb4 {30 years
ago Viktor Kupreichik invented this highly original and dangerous sacrifice.
He managed to completely confuse Epishin and win his game in great style in
only 26 moves! But nowadays, the right way for White is well known and it is a
rare guest in top-level games.} 8. Qxb4 e5 9. Qxb7 $1 (9. c5 exf4 10. exf4 b6
11. Ne5 bxc5 12. Qb7 Bd7 13. Nxd7 Nxd7 14. Qxc6 Rc8 15. Qxd5 cxd4 16. Bb5 Bb4+
17. Ke2 O-O $40 {Epishin,V -Kupreichik,V /Daugavpils 1989}) 9... Rb8 (9... exf4
$6 10. Ne5 $1) 10. Qxc6+ Bd7 11. Qa6 $1 (11. Qxf6 {This queen sacrifice looks
very tempting but it is not the best. White's king is way too vulnerable.} Qxf6
12. Bxe5 Qb6 13. b3 Qa5+ $1 14. Nbd2 Rxb3 15. Bxh8 Bb4 16. Be2 Bxd2+ 17. Nxd2
Rb2 18. O-O Rxd2 $15) 11... exf4 12. Nc3 fxe3 13. fxe3 Rxb2 (13... Bh6 {
The refutation of this move is not that easy to find:} 14. Qa3 $1 Bxe3 (14...
Qe7 15. Qxe7+ Kxe7 16. Nd1) 15. Ke2 Bh6 16. Re1 $1 $18) 14. c5 Bh6 15. Nd1 Qb8
16. Qa3 Qb4+ 17. Qxb4 Rxb4 18. Ne5 O-O 19. Bd3 $14 {, and I believe that
White's extra pawn is more valuable than Black's piece activity.}) (5... Qa5+
$6 {is rarely played and cannot be recommended. But to keep the advantage,
White must sacrifice a pawn:} 6. Nbd2 $1 dxc4 (6... Na6 7. a3 $1 dxc4 (7... Bf5
8. Qb3) 8. e4 $1 (8. Qxc4 Be6 9. Qc1 Nh5) 8... b5 9. Be2 $1 Bg7 (9... Qb6 10.
b3 cxb3 11. Nxb3 Bg7 12. Ne5 Bb7 13. Bd2 $1 $44) 10. b3 $1 c3 11. O-O Nh5 12.
Be3 $16) 7. e4 $1 b5 8. Be2 Bg7 9. O-O Nbd7 10. a4 Qb6 (10... Qd8 11. b3 $16)
11. b3 cxb3 12. Qxb3 $16 {Cifuentes Parada,R -Gomez Baillo,J Termas de Rio
Hondo 1987 ]}) 6. Qxc4 ({The pawn sacrifice} 6. e4 $6 b5 7. a4 a6 8. Nbd2 Bg7
9. b3 {is strongly refuted by} Nh5 $1 (9... cxb3 $6 10. Nxb3 $44 {Djukic,Z
-Perunovic,L / Nisa 2003}) 10. Be3 c5 $1 $36) 6... Bg7 (6... Be6 $5 {An
interesting alternative, which was analyzed by IM Quintillano in his wonderful
database for Modern Chess.} 7. Qc1 $1 ({The move} 7. Qc2 {is not very accurate.
} Bf5 $1 {The point of Black's idea.} 8. Qb3 Qb6 {It seems that Black solved
his problems. Few games continued:} 9. Nbd2 Nbd7 10. e3 Qxb3 11. Nxb3 a5 $1 {
With an equal game.}) 7... Bg7 (7... Na6 {doesn't seem to solve the opening
problems.} 8. Nc3 c5 9. e4 $1 $146 cxd4 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Nxd4 {White is at
least slightly better in this position.}) 8. Nc3 O-O 9. e4 Bg4 10. Be3 Bxf3 11.
gxf3 Nh5 (11... Nbd7 12. Be2 e5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Qc2 $14) 12. Qd2 e5 13. dxe5
Bxe5 (13... Qxd2+ 14. Kxd2 $1 Bxe5 15. Kc2 $1 Rd8 16. Ne2 {The position is
probably approximately equal, but it seems to me that White's play is easier.
The idea is f4 followed by e5.}) 14. O-O-O Qxd2+ (14... Qc7 15. Kb1 $14 {
Black has problems developing the queenside. White has the idea Ne2 followed
by f4. Also, White's queen has a nice spot on c1.}) 15. Rxd2) 7. Nc3 {This is
White's best choice, after which a sideline of the Russian System in the
Gruenfeld Defense arises. (5.Qb3 dxc4 6. Qxc4 c6 7.Bf4)} ({After other moves,
Black easily manages to play c6-c5, which equalizes comfortably.} 7. e3 O-O 8.
Nbd2 (8. Be2 Be6 9. Qc2 Nd5 ({or} 9... Bf5 10. Qc1 Nbd7 11. Nc3 c5 {Dubov,D
