Be5 Nxc3 11. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 12. Bxc3 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 dxc4 14. Bxc4 Nd7 $11) 10...
Nxc3 11. bxc3 Nd7 $1 (11... Bxc3+ 12. Nd2 Nd7 13. Be2 Nxc5 14. O-O $14) 12. e4
$5 $146 Nxc5 (12... Qxc3+ 13. Qxc3 Bxc3+ 14. Bd2 Bxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Nxc5 16. Ke3 f5
17. exf5 Bxf5 18. Bc4 Kg7 19. Nd4) 13. Be5 $1 {Exchanging the strong bishop on
g7 is an important achievement for White.} Bd7 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Rd4 $1 Na4 (
15... Rfc8 16. Qd2) 16. Bd3 Rac8 17. O-O Rxc3 18. Qd2 $36 {, and White's
pieces are ideally placed to create threats on the kingside by e4-e5 and Rh4.})
10. Bxc4 Qxc5 11. Qb3 $1 ({After} 11. Bb3 Nc6 (11... Bg4 $5 $146 {might be
simpler.} 12. O-O Nc6 13. Qe2 Nh5 $1) 12. O-O Bf5 13. Qe2 Rad8 (13... Nh5 14.
Bg5) 14. e4 $1 $146 {Black needs to find some very precise moves to keep the
balance.} (14. h3 Ne4 $1 $11 (14... h6 $6 15. e4 $16 {Bu Xiangzhi -Ibrahimov,R
/Riyadh KSA 2017/})) 14... Bg4 15. Rxd8 Rxd8 16. e5 Nh5 (16... Bxf3 17. Qxf3
Nxe5 18. Qxb7 Nd3 19. Be3) 17. Bxf7+ Kxf7 18. Be3 Qb4 19. a3 Qb3 20. Ng5+ Kg8
21. Qxg4 Bxe5 22. h3 Nf6 23. Qe2 Nd5 $1 $11) (11. Qe2 Bg4 $1 {or}) (11. Ne5 Nc6
$1 {are not dangerous for Black}) 11... Nc6 12. Ng5 $1 {White is aiming to
create a weakness on d6.} ({After the immediate} 12. Qb5 Qxb5 13. Bxb5 Bd7 (
13... Nh5 $5 14. Bg5 h6) 14. O-O Rac8 15. Rd2 a6 16. Be2 Bf5 17. h3 h6 18. g4
Be6 19. Rfd1 b5 20. Nd4 Nxd4 21. Rxd4 Ne8 22. Rd8 Rxd8 23. Rxd8 Nd6 $11 {
Black had a comfortable game in Le Quang,L -Tkachiev,V Khanty-Mansiysk 2009.})
12... e6 (12... Na5 $2 13. Bxf7+ Kh8 14. Qa4 h6 $140 15. Ne6 $16) 13. Qb5 (13.
Bb5 e5 $1 $11 {Le,Q -Chen,F /Beijing 2012}) (13. Nge4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Qa5+) 13...
Qxb5 14. Bxb5 h6 $1 $146 {is a strong improvement, having in mind that Nge4 is
impossible.} (14... e5 15. Bg3 h6 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Nf3 e4 18. Nd4 {led to a
very pleasant endgame in Peng, Z -Houska, J /Porto Carras 2011.}) 15. Nf3 (15.
