{[%evp 0,27,17,18,18,-16,39,29,25,-10,-3,-4,-7,-4,-4,-28,-24,-25,-35,-1,33,31,
22,-8,-8,-8,0,0,-3,-23]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 g6 5. cxd5 $5 {
We know that fixing the structure is White's best option in the 4.Qb3 g6 line.
But here the only advantage of 5.cd5 over 5.Bf4 is that White contains black
counterplay, avoiding the positions from the Gruenfeld Defence, where the
tension and the price of every move is very high. After 5.cd5, positions are
more in the spirit of the Exchange Slav. White is aiming to exploit the
passive position of Black's bishop on g7, which can be out of play for some
time. This is the preferred choice of Aronian, Artemiev, Ivanchuk, and Kamsky.}
cxd5 (5... Nxd5 $6 6. e4 {leads to a better version of the Gruenfeld Defence
for White.}) 6. Bf4 (6. Bg5 {was best after 4.Qb3 g6 5.cd5 cd5, but here it is
inferior, as Black has the obvious} Ne4 $1 7. Bf4 Nc6 8. Nc3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bg7
10. e3 Bf5 11. Qb3 Qd7 12. Be2 O-O 13. O-O Rfc8 14. Qb2 Na5 {, when Black had
a pleasant position in Temirbayev, S -Dreev, A Mumbai 2010.}) 6... Nc6 ({
It is too early for} 6... Bf5 $6 7. Qb3 $1 {, and after} Qb6 8. Qxb6 axb6 9.
Nc3 $14 {the endgame is quite unpleasant for Black.}) 7. e3 ({There is no time
for prophylactics.} 7. h3 Bf5 $1 8. Qb3 Na5 9. Qa4+ Bd7 $11) (7. Nc3 Nh5 $1 8.
Bg5 h6 9. Bd2 Bg7 10. Qb3 e6 11. g3 O-O 12. Bg2 b6 13. O-O Bb7 14. Rfc1 Nf6 $11
) 7... Bg7 (7... Nh5 $5 {is a good alternative, leading to more dynamic
positions.} 8. Be5 (8. Bg5 f6 $1 9. Bh4 Bf5 10. Qb3 g5 11. Bg3 Na5 12. Qa4+ Kf7
$1 13. Be2 Nxg3 14. hxg3 Rc8 15. Nc3 e6 $132) 8... f6 9. Bg3 {, and now Black
can try to get the initiative with} e5 $5 (9... Bf5 10. Qb3 Na5 11. Qa4+ Kf7 $5
) 10. dxe5 (10. Bb5 e4 11. Nfd2 Bd7 12. Nc3 Nxg3 13. hxg3 a6) (10. Nc3 e4 11.
Nd2 Be6 12. Be2 Nxg3 13. hxg3 f5 $13) 10... Nxg3 11. hxg3 fxe5 {It may look
like Black has the upper hand, building a strong centre and having the bishop
pair, but white has the unpleasant reply} 12. Bb5 $1 (12. Nc3 e4) 12... Bb4+
13. Nc3 O-O 14. O-O Bxc3 (14... e4 $2 15. Nxd5 $1 $16) (14... Bf5 15. Qb3 Bxc3
16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. Qxc3 e4 18. Nd4 $16) 15. Qxc3 e4 16. Nd4 Nxd4 17. Qxd4 Be6
18. Ba4 $14 {White has the advantage of the better bishop and the better pawn
structure.}) (7... Bf5 8. Qb3 Na5 {Quite similar type of play to the Exchange
Slav, the only difference being the bishop on g7. This gives White the chance
to exert some pressure, for example} 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Qa4 Rc8 11. Nc3 Nc6 12. h3
a6 13. Bxc6 Bxc6 14. Qb3 Bg7 15. O-O O-O 16. Rac1 e6 17. Ne5 Nd7 18. Nxc6 bxc6
19. Na4 e5 20. dxe5 Nxe5 21. Rfd1 $14) 8. Nc3 $1 ({Again there is no time for
the prophylactic move h2-h3.} 8. h3 Qb6 $1 9. Nc3 Bf5 10. Qb3 Qxb3 11. axb3 O-O
$11) 8... O-O ({Very interesting complications arise after} 8... Nh5 $5 {i} 9.
