{[%evp 0,39,21,5,30,-9,26,31,37,-3,21,-32,-14,-21,17,21,32,-3,0,8,8,1,0,18,-4,
-16,5,11,3,-7,5,19,22,22,22,-25,2,-31,-16,-10,16,29]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3
Nf6 4. Qc2 e6 5. Bg5 Nbd7 6. e3 Be7 7. Nc3 O-O {The starting position for the
classical Queen's gambit declined. It was the most popular opening position in
the first half of the 20th century and was intensively disputed in both world
championship matches Capablanca -Lasker and Alekhine -Capablanca. Black's
position is quite solid and he has a big variety of defensive plans: A) The
extended fiancheto with dc4 ,b5 and Bb7 followed by c6-c5 in very near future.
In this case, the inclusion of h7-h6 Bh4 is highly useful, as it avoids
White's attack on the h7 pawn. B) fianchetto of the queen's bishop with b6,
Bb7 followed by Rc8 and c6-c5, gradually equalising. This plan is the most
popular nowadays and its main promoter is M. Gurevich. C) The simplifying plan
dc4 followed by Nd5 - the classical treatment used by Lasker, Capablanca and
Alekhine. Black exchanges the dark-squared bishops, followed by the exchange
of the knights on c3. Then Black intends to complete development by b6-Bb7 and
c6-c5 or if possible by attacking the centre with e6-e5. Here Black usually
avoids the inclusion of h7-h6 to avoid the option of Bg3, preserving the
bishops. D) The useful waiting move a6, after which Black, depending on
circumstances, goes for either b7-b5, meeting c4-c5 with the central break
e6-e5, or looking to achieve a better version of the plan A) or B). E) The
simplifying manouevre Ne4 (usually with the inclusion of h7-h6 Bh4) - the
favourite plan of the world champion Lasker, which nowadays bears his name.} 8.
Rd1 $1 {This move is the prefered choice of the world champions Alekhine,
Capablanca, Kasparov as well as many other strong grandmasters. With this
useful move, White is fighting for a tempo, waiting for Black to take on c4.
At the same time, the rook d1 plays an active role in preventing Black from
active counterplay.} h6 ({Here adopting plan A) is not such a good idea.} 8...
dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nd5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O Nxc3 12. Qxc3 b6 (12... Re8 $6 13. Bb3
$1 {reveals the main idea of Rd1 - now the plan with e6-e5 is hardly possible.}
) (12... c5 $6 {It is a bit too early to open the center.} 13. Bb5 cxd4 (13...
b6 14. Bc6 Rb8 15. dxc5 Nxc5 (15... bxc5 16. b3 $14) 16. b4 $1 $36) 14. Qxd4
Nf6 15. Ne5 $1 a6 16. Be2 b5 17. Nc6 Qc7 {, and now in the game Sokolov,
I-Spycher, B Groningen 1986, White missed the winning idea} 18. Qc5 $1 Re8 19.
Rd8 $3 $18) 13. e4 $1 Bb7 14. Rfe1 Rac8 (14... c5 15. d5 $1 exd5 16. exd5 Qd6
17. Qe3 Nf6 18. Qe7 Qxe7 19. Rxe7 Rab8 20. d6 $16) (14... Nf6 15. Ne5 Rfd8 16.
f3 Nd7 (16... c5 17. d5 $1) 17. Ng4 Nf6 18. Ne3 $1 $14) 15. d5 $1 {I like this
idea and I believe it is the only chance to create some pressure. If White
misses this opportunity, Black will gradually equalise.} exd5 (15... e5 $6 {
was Black's reaction in the only game where d4-d5 was played.} 16. d6 Qf6 17.
Re3 Rcd8 18. g3 g6 19. b4 Kh8 20. h4 h6 21. Bf1 Qg7 22. Bh3 f6 23. h5 $18 {
White classicaly outplayed his oponent in Rueetschi,U -Plesec,D Switzerland
2002}) (15... cxd5 16. exd5 Nc5 17. d6 $1 {, creating a strong passed pawn.
Black's defensive task is quite complicated. For example} Qf6 18. Ne5 Rfd8 19.
d7 Nxd7 20. Nxd7 Qg5 21. Qg3 Qxg3 22. hxg3 Rxc4 23. Nf6+ gxf6 24. Rxd8+ Kg7 25.
Rd7 $18) 16. exd5 Qd6 17. Nd4 $1 {Only this move can justify the d4-d5 break.}
Qf6 (17... g6 18. dxc6) 18. d6 $3 {The following lines are very nice and
clearly show the tactical potential of the passed pawn.} (18. dxc6 {leads to a
better endgame by force.} Bxc6 19. Nxc6 Qxc6 20. Rc1 Qf6 21. Qxf6 Nxf6 22. Re7
$1 Nd5 23. Rb7 $1 Rc7 24. Rxc7 Nxc7 25. Kf1 g6 26. a3 Kg7 27. Rd1 b5 28. Ba2 a5
29. Rd7 $16) 18... Rce8 (18... Rcd8 19. Qg3 Rde8 (19... Rfe8 20. Re7 $1 $18)
20. Re7 Ne5 21. Bb3 $1 Rxe7 22. dxe7 Qxe7 23. Re1 Re8 24. f4 Qd7 25. Rd1 Ng6
26. f5 $16) 19. Re7 $1 Rxe7 20. dxe7 Re8 21. g4 $1 g6 22. Nf5 $18) (8... a6 $5
{plan D) - now White's best option is to continue in the same style with
another waiting move.} 9. a3 $1 {, played by Kasparov, Petrosian and Psakhis.
The idea is to get the retreat square a2 for the bishop, having in mind Ba2-b1.
} b5 (9... b6 10. Bd3 Bb7 11. O-O h6 12. Bh4 Rc8 {, when in the game
