17. Bd3 c5 18. d5 Qf6 $1 $11) 13... dxc4 (13... c5 $6 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5
exd5 16. dxc5 bxc5 17. Bf5 $14) (13... Nh5 14. Be5 $1 Nhf6 15. e4 dxc4 16. Bxc4
Nxe5 17. dxe5 Nd7 18. Nd4 $1 $40) 14. Bxc4 b5 15. Ba2 c5 (15... Qb6 16. e4 $1 (
16. b4 $6 a5 $1)) 16. d5 $1 exd5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Bxd5 19. Rxd5 Qe8 20.
Bd6 c4 21. Rfd1 Bxd6 22. Rxd6 Nc5 {Black is very close to equality, as the
activity of Black's knight provides good compensation for White's pressure on
the d-file. Nevertheless White managed to create some threats after} 23. Nd4 $5
g6 24. h4 {and later won the game.}) (9... h6 10. Bh4 b5 11. c5 Nh5 12. Bxe7
Qxe7 13. Be2 Nhf6 (13... e5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Bxh5 Qg5 16. f4) 14. e4 dxe4 15.
Nxe4 e5 16. O-O (16. Nd6 $5 $14) 16... exd4 17. Nxf6+ Nxf6 18. Nxd4 Bb7 19. Bf3
Qc7 20. Nf5 $16 {Tkachiev,V -Stanojoski,Z Skopje 2015}) (9... dxc4 $6 10. Bxc4
b5 11. Ba2 Bb7 12. Bb1 $1 {I very much like the following highly instructive
game Greenfeld, A -Djuric, S Rishon Le Ziyyon 1992, where White crushed the
opponent with the direct assault} g6 13. h4 $1 Ng4 (13... c5 14. dxc5 $1) 14.
Ne4 h6 15. Nd6 $3 hxg5 16. Nxf7 $18) 10. c5 $1 Nh5 {If Black plays b5 without
the inclusion of h6 Bh4, White can try the more aggressive} (10... e5 11. dxe5
Ng4 12. Bf4 Nxc5 13. h3 $16) (10... h6 11. Bf4 Nh5 12. Be5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bb7)
11. h4 $1 (11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Be2 $14 e5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Bxh5 Qg5 15. f4 Qxh5
16. dxe5 f6 17. exf6 Rxf6 18. Rd4 Bf5 19. Qe2 Qg6) 11... f5 (11... h6 12. g4 $1
Nhf6 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. g5) 12. Be2 Nhf6 13. Na2 $5 $146 {White's standard plan
of taking the darks squares is very effective here. The knight goes to c1-d3
and then to e5 or f4.} (13. b4 Ne4 14. Bf4 $14 {De Haan,E -Sonntag,H Antwerp
2000}) 13... a5 14. Nc1 Ba6 (14... b4 15. Nd3 bxa3 16. Nf4) 15. Nd3 Qe8 (15...
b4 16. Nf4) 16. b4 $1 $16 {, with a huge space advantage for White.}) 9. Bh4 b6
$1 {Plan B) is definitely the most solid black continuation.} ({Lasker's plan
is now out of the question, as Black will just lose a pawn after} 9... Ne4 10.
Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Qxe4 Qb4+ 13. Rd2 $1 {One more idea of the clever
move Rd1.}) 10. Be2 {White doesn't have a big choice.} ({Fixing the structure
with} 10. cxd5 $5 {is an alternative way, but I think in this case White can
enjoy only a very tiny edge.} cxd5 $1 (10... exd5 $6 {In the Karlsbad
structure with the weakness on c6, White has clear advantage.} 11. Bd3 Bb7 12.
O-O Re8 13. Bg3 Nh5 (13... Nf8 14. h3 Bd6 15. Ne5 $16) 14. Be5 $1 Nhf6 (14...
Nxe5 $2 15. dxe5 $1 Bc8 16. Nd4 Bd7 17. Be2 g6 18. e6 $18 {Miles,A -Afifi,A
Tunis 1985}) 15. e4 $5 (15. h3 {Popovich,S -Durnev,V Lvov 2010}) 15... dxe4 16.
Nxe4 $14) 11. Bd3 Bb7 12. O-O Rc8 13. Qb1 a6 14. Rc1 Bd6 15. Bg3 Qe7 16. Bxd6
Qxd6 17. Rc2 Rc7 18. Rfc1 Rfc8 19. a3 $11 {White's bishop on d3 is much better
than Black's on b7, but it's insuffcient to claim an advantage.}) (10. Bd3 {
is less precise as White doesn't have the option of Ne5.} Bb7 11. O-O Rc8 12.
e4 (12. Bg3 Nh5 $11 {Riazantsev,A -Kharitonov,A Hengelo 2005} 13. Be5 Nhf6 14.
h3 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nd7 $11) (12. Qe2 Ne4 $5 13. Bg3 (13. Bxe7 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Qxe7
$11) 13... Nxg3 14. hxg3 dxc4 15. Bxc4 b5 16. Bd3 a6 (16... b4 17. Ne4 Qb6 $11
{Zhukova,N -Ambarcumova,K Moscow 2009})) (12. Ne5 $6 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Ng4) 12...
dxc4 13. Bxc4 b5 14. Bd3 b4 15. Na4 c5 $11) 10... Bb7 (10... Ba6 11. b3 $1 Rc8
12. O-O c5 $5) 11. O-O Rc8 12. Ne5 $1 (12. Bg3 Nh5 13. Be5 Nhf6) (12. Qa4 a6
13. Qb3 dxc4 14. Bxc4 b5 15. a4) (12. a3 c5 13. dxc5 Rxc5) (12. Qb1 c5 13. cxd5
Nxd5 14. Bg3 N7f6 15. dxc5 Rxc5 16. Nb5 a6 17. Nbd4 Qa8) 12... Nxe5 (12... c5
13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. dxc5 $14) 13. dxe5 Nd7 14. Bg3 $1
Bh4 $1 (14... Bb4 15. a3 Bxc3 16. Qxc3 a5 17. b4 $1 $146 {Restricting the
