{[%evp 0,31,21,30,30,-9,26,19,30,-19,21,-32,-14,-40,-8,-26,-8,-2,3,3,7,-3,14,
-14,29,25,35,33,24,27,26,29,25,37]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 e6 5.
Bg5 Nbd7 6. Nbd2 {The main aim of this move is to avoid the complications
arising after 6.e3 Qa5. The negative side is that White's options to create
pressure in the classical QGD with Nd2 are quite limited.} Be7 (6... Qa5 {
is not anymore effective because of} 7. a3 $1 {This way White frees the rook
from the defence of the pawn and also takes control over the b4-square.} Ne4 8.
Bf4 $1 (8. Bh4 h6 $1) 8... Be7 $1 {Preparing g5. Now I propose the logical and
strong novelty} ({The immediate} 8... g5 $6 {does not work because of} 9. cxd5
$1 cxd5 10. Nxg5 $16) 9. g3 $1 $146 {The idea is to keep e3 as a retreat
square for the bishop.} f5 (9... g5 $6 10. Be3 f5 11. h4 $1) 10. h4 $1 O-O 11.
Bg2 h6 12. Rd1 Bf6 13. O-O Qd8 14. Nxe4 $1 fxe4 (14... dxe4 15. Ne5 g5 16. Bd2
Qc7 17. hxg5 hxg5 18. Qc1 $1 $36) 15. Ne5 Bxh4 (15... Bxe5 16. dxe5 g5 17. hxg5
hxg5 18. Be3 Nxe5 19. Bxe4 $18) 16. Ng6 Rf6 17. Nxh4 Rxf4 18. gxf4 Qxh4 19. e3
Nf6 20. f3 $16 {, and Black has no compensation for the exchange.}) ({After} 
6... h6 7. Bxf6 $5 Nxf6 8. g3 Bd6 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O b6 {we have a Catalan
opening where White enjoys a risk-free advantage. The game Yuffa, D-Mamedyarov,
S Moscow 2017 continued} 11. e4 dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Bb7 14. Rfd1 Qe7
15. Ne5 Rac8 16. Rac1 ({Missing the typical} 16. c5 $1 Bxe5 17. Qxe5 Rfd8 18.
Rac1 $14) 16... Rfd8 17. a3 a5 (17... Ba8 18. Qe3 c5 19. Bxa8 Bxe5) 18. Qe3 a4
$6 (18... c5 $1 $11) 19. c5 $1 bxc5 20. dxc5 Bxe5 21. Qxe5 Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 Ba6
23. Rd6 $14 {, and Black's defence is not at all simple.}) 7. g3 $1 {The
fianchetto of the king's bishop is the only way to fight for an advantage, as
in the classical QGD positions with a knight on d2 Black solves his opening
problems fairly easily.} (7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3 (8. Be2 h6 {followed by c5 brings
Black the desired equality.} 9. Bh4 (9. Bf4 c5 10. cxd5 (10. dxc5 Nxc5 11. O-O
b6) 10... Nxd5 11. Bg3 b6 12. O-O Bb7 13. Rad1 Rc8 14. Qb1 N5f6 15. h3 a6 $1 {
Intending b5, Qb6.} 16. a4 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Nc5 $11) 9... c5 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Bg3
b6 12. Rc1 Bb7 13. O-O {Now in the game Gurevich, M-Malakhov, V /Saint Vincent
2002, Black could have played} Rc8 14. Qb1 N5f6 $1 15. h3 a6 $11) 8... h6 $1 {
Again the inclusion of h6 Bh4 is obligatory.} (8... dxc4 $6 9. Nxc4 b5 10. Nce5
) (8... b6 $6 9. Ne5 Bb7 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Nxd7) 9. Bh4 (9. Bf4 c5 $1 10. O-O
b6 $11) 9... c5 (9... b6 10. cxd5 Nxd5 (10... cxd5 11. O-O Bb7 12. Rfc1 Bd6 13.
Bg3 Bxg3 14. hxg3 Rc8 15. Qa4 a6 $11) 11. Bxe7 Nxe7 12. O-O c5 $11) 10. Bxf6 (
10. O-O b6 11. Rac1 Bb7 $11) 10... Nxf6 $1 (10... Bxf6 11. cxd5 exd5 12. dxc5
Qa5 13. O-O Nxc5 14. Nb3 Nxb3 15. Qxb3 Be6 16. Nd4 $14) 11. dxc5 dxc4 12. Qxc4
(12. Nxc4 Bxc5 13. O-O b6 14. Rfd1 Qe7 15. a3 a5 $11) 12... Bxc5 {In the game
Samdanov, S -Sanzhaev, D Maribor 2012, after a couple of precise moves Black
was able to equalize.} 13. O-O Qe7 14. Rac1 b6 15. Ne4 Nd7 ({or} 15... Bb7 16.
Nxc5 Rfc8 17. Qb5 Rxc5 18. Rxc5 bxc5 19. Nd2 Rd8 20. Rd1 Ng4 21. Nf1 Ne5 22.
Be2 Rxd1 23. Bxd1 Qc7 $11) 16. a3 a5 17. Qa4 (17. Rfd1 Bb7 18. Nxc5 Nxc5) 17...
Bb7 18. Bb5 Bxe4 19. Qxe4 Nf6 $11) 7... O-O 8. Bg2 b6 9. O-O Bb7 {We reached a
position quite typical for the Catalan opening.} 10. Rad1 $1 (10. Rac1 c5 11.
Rfd1 Rc8 $11) ({In case of the direct} 10. e4 {Black equalises with} dxe4 11.
Nxe4 c5 $1 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Ng5 Qxg5 15. Bxb7 Rab8 16. Bc6 Rbd8
17. Rad1 Nf6 18. dxc5 Qxc5 19. Bg2 b5 $11) 10... Rc8 (10... h6 $5 11. Bxf6 (11.
Bf4 c5 $1) 11... Nxf6 12. e4 Rc8 13. Rfe1 $14) 11. e4 {Now White can increase
the pressure.} Nxe4 (11... c5 12. exd5 exd5 13. dxc5 $1 Nxc5 14. Nd4 $1 {
, and Black had great problems in Werle, J - Sipke,E -Groningeen 2003.} Qd7 ({
or} 14... Re8 15. Nf5 Bf8 16. Ne3 $1) 15. Nf5 $16) (11... h6 12. Bf4 $1 $36)
12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Qxe4 Nf6 15. Qe2 Rfd8 16. Rfe1 {, resulting in
a typical risk-free position for White who has a space advantage. Kosic,D -Yu,
L Kecskemet 2010} *

