{[%evp 0,41,30,30,20,-17,34,30,19,3,1,-20,29,26,20,-4,-4,34,-10,-10,4,12,12,
-11,-11,8,1,0,0,7,0,-10,-8,-1,-1,3,3,1,-19,-37,-30,-23,-17,-48]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4
c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qb3 dxc4 5. Qxc4 Bg4 {The system with the bishop development
to Bg4 is more aggressive compared to Bf5. Besides, it is not yet so deeply
analysed and there are many new ideas for both sides. After 5...Bg4 White has
a choice between the sharp 6.Nc3 and the more restrained 6.Nbd2. The line with
6.Nc3 is more aggressive and double-edged. In my view, Black should better
refrain from an early exchange on f3, as then White's piece activity prevails
over the defects of the pawn structure. My personal preference is for the more
solid 6.Nbd2, which is more in the spirit of the opening system. I had the
impression that the best option for White is 10.Qb3, but after some deep
analysis, I think that it is nothing better than the other lines with 10.b3
and 10.Ne5. White's main aim in the following lines is to isolate Black's
queen's bishop on g6. To improve your understanding of positions of this type,
you may like to visit the pawn structure section.} 6. Nc3 Nbd7 $1 {[%eval 401,
0] .The immediate} (6... Bxf3 {[%eval 401,0] in my opinion is significantly
worse and offers White excellent attacking chances.}) (6... e6 {is too passive.
} 7. e4 b5 8. Qd3 b4 9. Na4 Nbd7 10. Be3 Be7 11. Rc1 $14) 7. Bf4 {After some
time White players understood that in the line 7.e4 e5! Black is doing fine
and they started looking for new ideas. 7.Bf4 is an important novelty
introduced at the top level by Mamedyarov in a blitz game in 2011 against Le
Quang and then in classical time control against Yilmaz in 2014 Turkish team
championship. Nowadays it became the established mainline. The idea of Bf4 is
obviously to prevent e5.} ({The most amazing complications starts after} 7. e4
e5 $1 {This is the idea introduced by Magnus Carlsen against Nyback at the
2014 Chess Olympiad. It is connected with a piece sacrifice which by force
leads to a draw by repetition. The mainline goes} 8. dxe5 (8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. dxe5
Be6 10. Qd3 (10. Qa4 Ng4 11. Be2 Nxe5 12. O-O Bc5 $11 {Raetsky,A -Nasuta,G
Newcastle ENG 2018}) (10. Qe2 Ng4) 10... Ng4 11. Qxd8+ Rxd8 12. Bf4 $1 (12. f4
Bc5 $36) 12... Bc5 13. Bg3 Bd4 14. Rd1 Bxe5 $11 {Nyback,T -Carlsen,M Tromso 
(ol) 2014}) ({The normal looking} 8. Be3 {suddenly puts White in an unpleasant
situation.} Qa5 $1 9. Bd3 (9. dxe5 Be6 $1 10. Qa4 (10. Qd3 Ng4) 10... Qxa4 11.
Nxa4 Nxe4 $15) 9... Bxf3 10. gxf3 Nb6 11. Qb3 exd4 12. Bxd4 Rd8 $17) 8... Bxf3
9. exf6 $5 (9. gxf3 Nxe5 $11 {Donchenko,A -Yilmaz, M Biel SUI 2015} 10. Qe2 Bc5
$1 11. Bd2 Nh5 {Take a look at the amazing game Hoang Thanh Trang - Barbosa, O
- Jakarta 2013.}) 9... Qxf6 {Gasanov,E -Gajwa,A New Delhi IND 2015 Accepting
the sacrifice leads to a draw by repetition.} 10. gxf3 (10. Be3 Bg4 $11) 10...
Ne5 11. Qa4 Nxf3+ 12. Kd1 (12. Ke2 Nd4+ 13. Kd3 Rd8 14. Be3 Bc5 15. Nd5 Ne6 16.
Kc2 Qf3 17. Bd3 O-O) 12... Rd8+ 13. Kc2 Nd4+ 14. Kb1 Qf3 15. Rg1 Qxf2 16. Rh1
Qf3 $11) 7... Nb6 {This is the only way Black can generate some counterplay,
trying to prevent the bind.} (7... Qb6 {is hardly a good option, as Black is
not really threatening to take on b2.} 8. e4 $1 {More precise than} (8. O-O-O {
Wang Yue -Bhat, V chess.com INT 2019} Nd5 $1) 8... e5 (8... Qxb2 $6 9. Rb1 Qa3
10. Rxb7 $36) 9. dxe5 Nh5 10. Be3 Bc5 11. Na4 Bb4+ (11... Qb4+ $6 12. Qxb4
Bxb4+ 13. Nd2 Nxe5 14. a3 Ba5 15. h3 Be6 16. b4 Bc7 17. g4 Nf6 18. f4 $18) 12.
Nd2 Qa5 13. a3 Bxd2+ 14. Bxd2 Qxe5 15. f3 Be6 16. Qc3 Qxc3 17. Nxc3 $14 {
With a pleasant advantage for White in the endgame.}) (7... Qa5 $5 $146 {
is an interesting novelty.} 8. Qb3 $1 Qb6 (8... O-O-O {leads to an original
and very fresh position. In my opinion, it is not any worse than the mainline.}
9. O-O-O e6 10. Nd2 (10. e4 Bb4) 10... Nb6 $11) 9. e4 Qxb3 10. axb3 Bxf3 11.
gxf3 e6 $11 {, and the endgame is balanced - White's pawn weaknesses are
compensated by the bishop pair and the strong centre.} ({But not} 11... e5 $2
12. dxe5 Nh5 13. Be3 Nxe5 14. Ra5 $1 $18 {Leitao-El Debs 2013})) (7... Bxf3 8.
gxf3 Nb6 9. Qd3 Nfd5 10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. Bd2 e6 12. e4 Nf6 13. O-O-O g6 14. Kb1
Bg7 15. Be3 O-O 16. Be2 Qc7 17. h4 $14 {was great for White in Jumabayev, R
-Matlakov, M Tallinn EST 2016.}) (7... e6 8. e4 Be7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Rc8 $14
{White maintained his strong pawn centre and had the better chances in
Donchenko, A -Gledura, B Zalakaros HUN 2014.}) 8. Qd3 Nbd5 9. Nxd5 (9. Be5 Qb6
$1 10. Rb1 Nd7 11. Bg3 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Nb4 13. Qd2 Qxd4 $1) 9... Qxd5 10. Ne5 ({
Worth investigating is} 10. Nd2 $5 Bf5 11. Qc3 {, with the idea f3, e4.}) 10...
Be6 $1 (10... Rd8 {is weaker.} 11. e3 $1 (11. Nxg4 $6 Nxg4 12. e3 (12. f3 e5
13. Bd2 {Dvirnyy,D -Sonis,F Alessandria ITA 2018} e4 $1 14. fxe4 Qxd4) 12... e5
) 11... e6 (11... Be6 $5 12. Qa3 Nh5 13. Bg3 $14) 12. f3 $1 Bb4+ 13. Kf2 Bf5
14. Qb3 ({even better was} 14. Qd1 O-O 15. g4 Bg6 16. h4 $5 $40) 14... Qxb3 15.
axb3 {, and the endgame is very difficult for Black. After} a6 16. Bxa6 $1 $18
{Black's position fell apart in Mamedyarov,S -Yilmaz,M Kocaeli TUR 2014.}) 11.
f3 Rd8 12. e4 Qxd4 13. Qxd4 Rxd4 14. Be3 Rd6 15. Bxa7 Nd7 $1 16. Nc4 $1 $146 {
improving on} (16. Nxd7 $11 {Georgiadis,N- Gonda.L - 2016 ch AUS}) 16... Bxc4
17. Bxc4 g6 18. Ke2 Bg7 19. a4 O-O 20. Be3 Ne5 21. Ba2 $14 {I think that Black
needs to play carefully to maintain the balance. White's idea is to expand in
the centre with f4, e5.} *

