{[%evp 0,37,20,22,13,-20,26,30,29,3,-20,-37,26,20,32,21,32,28,28,37,37,50,50,
44,34,-2,19,28,17,35,38,29,27,16,31,23,69,52,36,5]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3
Nf6 4. Qb3 dxc4 5. Qxc4 Bg4 6. Nc3 Bxf3 7. gxf3 Nbd7 {The line with 6...Bf3
leads to unbalanced positions. White pawn structure has been compromised, but
his bishop pair together with the pressure on both the open d-file and
semi-open g-file after 0-0-0 provide him with excellent attacking chances.} (
7... g6 8. e4 Bg7 9. Be3 O-O $14 {Those positions are more typical for the
Gruenfeld Defence and are considered quite pleasant for White because of the
powerful centre and better attacking perspectives - see Short,N -Baburin,A
Bunratty IRL 2017.}) 8. e4 (8. f4 $5 {is worth investigating, as White
prevents the e5 break, maintaining his space advantage.} g6 (8... e6 9. Bd2 Rc8
10. Bg2 Be7 11. O-O $14) 9. Bg2 (9. e4 $6 Bh6) 9... Nb6 10. Qd3 Bg7 11. O-O e6
12. Rd1 O-O 13. Qh3 $14 {White has plenty of time to improve his pieces, as it
is difficult for Black to display any activity. The only issue to solve is how
to open up the position. The only way is to play e2-e4 at some point but it
creates a weakness on f4.}) 8... e5 (8... g6 9. Be3 Bg7 10. O-O-O O-O 11. Kb1
$14) 9. Be3 exd4 $1 {The battle for the dark squares d4 and e5 begins. I think
it is the best moment for Black to exchange on d4 now, as it deflects the
bishop e3 from the defence of the f4 square. At a later time, White may be
able to take back with the queen or knight (after Ne2) .} (9... Bd6 {Normal
development is also acceptable, but then Black might have problems achieving
his best setup.} 10. O-O-O Qe7 (10... Qc7 11. dxe5 $1 {is a very strong idea.}
Bxe5 {Now White has very strong pressure:} 12. Ne2 (12. Bh3 b5 (12... Nf8 $2
13. f4 $1 {Ortega,M -Miranda Mesa,E Varadero CUB 2016} Bxf4 14. e5 $3 Bxe5 15.
Rhe1) 13. Qd3 Nb6) 12... Nh5 (12... Nb6 13. Qb4) 13. Kb1 Ndf6 14. Qc1 $1 Bd6
15. Bg2 g6 16. f4 Ng4 17. Bd4 Rg8 18. Bf3 $18 {Baryshpolets,A -Vysochin,S Kyiv
UKR 2015}) (10... exd4 $6 {is already an error because of} 11. Qxd4 $1 Be5 (
11... Bc5 $2 12. Qxc5 $18) 12. Qb4 $1 a5 13. Qa3 Qe7 (13... b5 14. Ne2) 14.
Qxe7+ Kxe7 15. f4 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Nxe4 17. Bh3 Nef6 18. Rhe1 $16 {is nearly
winning for White.}) 11. Ne2 $1 {Now taking on d4 is not an option anymore as
White will meet it with Nd4!} g6 (11... Qe6 12. Qxe6+ fxe6 13. dxe5 Bxe5 14. f4
Bc7 15. Nd4 Ke7 16. Bc4 Nb6 17. Bb3 $18 {Fridman,D -Ipatov,A Rabat MAR 2014}) (
11... O-O 12. Ng3 g6 13. Rg1 Kh8 14. Bg5 exd4 15. Qxd4 Be5 16. Qd2 $16) 12. Bh3
Rd8 13. Kb1 (13. Bh6 $1 $16) 13... Nb6 14. Qc2 exd4 15. Nxd4 O-O 16. Bh6 Rfe8 {
, and now in Laxman, D - Ghosh, D 49 Ind ch - 2011} 17. Nf5 $1 {could have
finished the game by direct attack.} Qe5 18. Bg5 Bc7 (18... gxf5 19. Rhg1 Kh8
20. f4 $18) 19. Nh6+ Kg7 20. Rdg1 $18) (9... Nh5 $6 {This move is extremely
risky for Black. The idea to create an outpost on the dark squares is
reasonable from a strategical point of view, but being so much behind in
development in an open position is not recommendable.} 10. O-O-O Qf6 11. dxe5 (
11. Bh3 $5) 11... Nxe5 12. Qb3 Bd6 13. Kb1 $1 {, and Black cannot maintain the
blockade.} (13. f4 {White wins material but releases the pressure too early.}
Nxf4 14. Rxd6 Qxd6 15. Bxf4 Nd3+ 16. Bxd3 Qxf4+ 17. Kb1 O-O-O 18. Na4 Rd4 (
18... Qxf2 19. Rc1) 19. Rc1 Rhd8 20. Bc2 $14) 13... Qe7 (13... O-O $2 14. f4
Nxf4 15. Rxd6 $18) (13... Rd8 14. Bxa7 O-O 15. Bb6 $16) 14. f4 Ng6 15. e5 Bb4
16. Rd4 $18 {Rasmussen,A -Matthiesen,M Denmark DEN 2019}) (9... Qa5 10. O-O-O
Bb4 {is easily parried by} 11. a3 Be7 (11... Bxc3 12. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 13. bxc3 O-O
14. Kc2 $16 {with a strong centre and the bishop pair, White will have a huge
advantage.}) 12. Rg1 g6 13. f4 $1 exf4 14. Bxf4 O-O 15. Qb3 b5 16. e5 Nh5 17.
Bd2 Ng7 18. Bh3 Qc7 19. f4 $16 {, with a crushing initiative in Simic,
R-Pastar, S Belgrade SRB 2015.}) (9... Nb6 $6 {is obviously wrong, as Black's
knight has nothing to do on b6.} 10. Qd3 $1 (10. Qb3 exd4 11. O-O-O c5 12. Bb5+
Nfd7 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Qc7 {is not that clear.}) 10... Bd6 11. O-O-O Qc7
12. Rg1 $40) 10. Bxd4 (10. Qxd4 Bc5 11. Qd2 Qe7 $11 {followed by long castle
is good for Black.}) 10... Bd6 11. O-O-O Qc7 {It looks like Black enjoys a
nice grip on the dark squares f4 and e5 and may easily establish a blockade.
But thanks to his piece activity White can prevent this by simple means.} (
11... Qe7 12. Ne2 $1 {White is improving his badly placed knight, rerouting it
to g3.} O-O (12... Bc5 $5) 13. Ng3 g6 14. Rg1 Kh8 15. Kb1 (15. Be3 $5) 15...
Be5 (15... Bc5 16. Bc3 Rfd8) 16. Be3 Nb6 17. Qc2 Rad8 18. Be2 (18. Bd3) 18...
Qc7 19. h4 $16 {White achieved typical pressure in Bivol, A -Baraeva, I Loo
RUS 2014.}) 12. Ne2 $1 O-O 13. Qc2 $1 {This is the most precise move, keeping
the queen away from the range of the Black knights.} (13. Kb1 {wasted an
important tempo in Epishin-Viebe Germany 2014.} c5 14. Be3 Ne5) 13... Rad8 {
This is the critical position for line 4.1.2 6...Bf3. The statistics are
clearly in White favour. The main action in the middlegame will be on the
kingside, so White's king on b1 is out of danger. In my database, I found two
games from 2013: Handke, F -Janusz,T Germany 2013 and Blomqvist, E -Smith, A
Gothenburg 2013. In both of them White won convincingly.} (13... c5 $6 14. Be3
Ne5 $2 15. f4 $1 $18) 14. Be3 {, with the idea to play f3-f4, rolling the
pawns forward.} Nh5 $5 (14... Rfe8 15. Kb1 Nf8 (15... Ne5 $6 16. f4 Neg4 17. e5
$16) 16. h4 Nh5 17. Nd4 (17. Bh3 Ne6 (17... Be5 $5 {Garcia Roman,D -Arizmendi
Martinez,J Mislata 2010} 18. Bg4 $14) 18. Bxe6 $1 fxe6 (18... Rxe6 $6 19. f4)
19. Qb3 $1 (19. Rd3) 19... c5 20. Rd2 Bf8 21. Rxd8 Qxd8 22. Rd1 $14 {Blomqvist,
E -Smith,A Gothenburg 2013}) 17... Be5 18. Bc4 Rd7 19. Nf5 Red8 20. Rdg1 (20.
Rxd7 Rxd7 21. Rg1 $5) 20... Ne6 $2 (20... Kh8 $1 $13) 21. Nh6+ Kf8 22. Bxe6
fxe6 23. Ng4 $16 {Handke,F -Banusz,T Germany 2013}) 15. Kb1 $1 {This important
prophylactic move prevents Black's invasion on f4.} (15. Bh3 Nf4 $1) 15... Ndf6
(15... Bxh2 $2 16. e5) (15... Nf4 $2 16. Rxd6 $1) 16. h4 (16. Qc1 Rfe8 17. h4)
16... Rfe8 17. Bh3 $1 {White finally completed his development. All his pieces
are active, while Black has to be in constant alert, as his king is placed on
an open file. White can increase the pressure either by doubling rooks on the
g-file or by Bg4 and Nd4-f5.} (17. Qc1 c5 18. Bh3 b5 19. Bg4 $14) 17... Bf4 18.
Nxf4 Nxf4 19. Rdg1 $36 {White has very strong pressure.} *

