{[%evp 0,41,30,30,13,-13,26,29,34,-20,-20,-31,29,9,14,-38,-30,-35,-2,-13,10,
-15,-3,-5,0,30,14,16,28,26,15,15,17,32,26,7,20,24,-4,18,16,4,4,-8]} 1. d4 d5 2.
c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 dxc4 5. Qxc4 Bg4 {A)} 6. Nbd2 {This is a more
positional approach. White prevents Bf3, aiming to complete development with
g3, Bg2, 0-0.} ({It is too early for} 6. Ne5 {Dimitrov,R -Delchev, A Sunny
Beach 2015} Be6 $1 7. Qd3 Nbd7 8. e4 $6 (8. Nf3 Bg4 9. Nc3 (9. e4 $6 Bxf3 10.
Qxf3 e5 $15) 9... Qb6 $11) 8... Nxe5 9. dxe5 Qxd3 10. Bxd3 Nd7 11. f4 g5 $1 {
Black already has the initiative.} 12. g3 gxf4 13. gxf4 Bh6 (13... O-O-O 14.
Be2 f5 $5 $36) 14. Nc3 O-O-O 15. Be2 f5 16. exf6 exf6 17. Kf2 f5 18. e5 Nf8 19.
Be3 Ng6 20. Kf3 Nh4+ 21. Kg3 Ng6 {, and here the draw was signed.}) 6... e6 {
This slight inaccuracy gives White an interesting choice.} (6... Nbd7 $1 {
is the more precise move.}) 7. g3 ({I think} 7. Ne5 $5 {is a good attempt to
punish Black for the wrong move order.} Bh5 $1 (7... Bf5 8. Qb3 $1 $146 (8. f3
$2 b5) 8... Qb6 (8... Qc7 9. f3 Nbd7 10. e4 $14) 9. f3 {followed by e4, and
White should be better.} Nbd7 10. e4 Bg6 11. Ndc4 Qxb3 12. axb3 Bb4+ 13. Kf2
$14 {White has a strong initiative in the endgame.}) 8. e4 (8. h3 Nbd7 9. g4
Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Bg2 Qc7 $11) 8... Nbd7 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. Bd3 $5 {is worth
investigating, for example} (10. f3 {[%cal Rf1g2,Rf1c4]} Rd8 11. Nb3 e5 12. Bg5
exd4 13. O-O-O $36 {is also very strong.}) 10... Rd8 11. Nb3 Bg6 12. f3 e5 13.
Be3 $16 {, and the bishop is buried on g6.}) 7... Nbd7 8. Bg2 Be7 (8... Nb6 9.
Qb3 $1 {leads to the line 4.2.1 10 Qb3, but White can also try} (9. Qd3 $5 Be7
10. O-O O-O 11. Ne5 Bh5 12. Ndf3 $14)) 9. O-O O-O {[%emt 0:00:10] We arrived
at the main position. White is at a crossroads. A couple of years ago I was
convinced that the mainline starts with Qb3, but some recent games show that
the other moves are equally interesting, so I decided to include 10 b3 and 10
Ne5.} 10. Qb3 b5 $5 {In fact when I started investigating the 4.Qc2 Slav I
didn't analyse this move at all, but now I think that it might be Black best
chance to create counterplay. It was first played in the game Batsiashvili, N
-Brunello, M Riga LAT 2017. Black's idea is to continue with Qb6, Rac8 and
c6-c5, not fearing the weakness on c6. The only downside of b5 is that opening
the long diagonal comes as pleasant news for White's Bg2, which was so far
biting the b7-c6 barrier.} (10... Nb6 $6 {is too passive. White gets what he
wants:} 11. a4 $1 a5 (11... Qd5 12. a5 Qxb3 13. Nxb3 $36) 12. Rd1 $1 {It is
difficult for Black is to achieve active counterplay, as the b6 knight is
hanging.} Rc8 13. h3 Bh5 14. g4 Bg6 15. Ne5 Nfd5 16. e4 Nb4 17. Nf1 $16) (10...
Qb6 {is the most often played move here, and probably also the most solid one.}
11. Nc4 $1 Qa6 $1 {Black will do better to avoid the endgame.} (11... Qxb3 $6
12. axb3 {The endgame is very pleasant for White.} Bb4 $1 {Otherwise Na5 is
coming.} (12... c5 $6 {Istratescu,A -Nanu, C Vaujany 2011} 13. Bf4 $1 Nd5 14.
Bd6 $14) 13. h3 (13. Na5 Bxa5 14. Rxa5 $14) 13... Bh5 14. g4 Bg6 15. Bd2 Bxd2
16. Nfxd2 $14 {, with some pressure for White.}) 12. Bd2 $5 {This is a more
concrete setup. Rfc1 and then e3, Bf1, after which the black queen is in
danger.} (12. Re1 {Defending the pawn and planning e4 and Bf1 is too slow:}
Rfd8 $1 (12... Nb6 13. Nce5 $1) 13. Bd2 (13. e4 $6 c5 $1) (13. Bf4 Bxf3 14.
Bxf3 Nb6 $11 {Harikrishna,P -Kasimdzhanov,R Nancy 2011}) (13. e3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3
b5 15. Nd2 Rac8 $132) 13... Nb6 (13... c5 $6 14. Nfe5) (13... Rac8 $11) (13...
b5 14. Nce5 Bxf3 15. Nxf3 c5 $11) 14. Nce5 Bxf3 15. Nxf3 c5 (15... Ne4 16. Be3
$14) 16. dxc5 Bxc5 17. Bg5 Nbd7 18. Rac1 Rac8 19. Nd2 b5 20. Ne4 Be7 $11) 12...
Nb6 $1 {is Black's only move, aiming for exchanges while the e2 pawn is still
unprotected.} (12... Nd5 $6 13. e4 N5b6 14. Ne3 Bh5 15. a4 $16) (12... Rad8 13.
Rfc1 $1 c5 (13... Nb6 14. e3 Nxc4 15. Rxc4 $14) 14. e3 cxd4 (14... b5 15. Nce5
Bf5 16. a4 (16. Nxd7 Nxd7 17. a4) 16... b4 17. Nxd7 Nxd7 18. dxc5 Nxc5 19. Qxb4
$16) 15. Nxd4 Nc5 16. Qc2 $14) (12... Rac8 13. Rfc1 Nb6 14. e3 $1 Nxc4 (14...
c5 $6 15. Nce5) (14... Nfd7 15. Na5 $36) 15. Rxc4 b5 16. Rcc1 Nd7 17. Bb4 $1 (
17. a4) 17... c5 18. dxc5 Bxc5 19. Rc3 $14) 13. Rfc1 Nxc4 (13... Rfd8 14. e3
$14) 14. Rxc4 Ne4 15. Be1 Nd6 $1 16. Ra4 {, and now to be able to equalise,
Black has to play a number of only moves, starting with bravely taking the e2
pawn.} Qxe2 $1 17. d5 Ne4 $8 18. Nd4 Nc5 $8 19. Nxe2 Nxb3 20. axb3 Bxe2 21.
dxc6 bxc6 22. Bxc6 (22. Rxa7 Rxa7 23. Rxa7 Bc5 $11) 22... Rac8 23. Bd7 Rc2 24.
Rxa7 Bf6 25. b4 Bxb2 26. Ba4 Rcc8 27. Rb1 Bd4 28. Rd7 e5 {Although White has a
distant passed pawn, the endgame should be ok for Black.}) 11. h3 (11. a4 a6
12. Ne5 $6 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. e4 Nb4 $15 {was bad for White in Ippolito, D
-Li, R Las Vegas USA 2019.}) 11... Bh5 12. g4 $5 {is the obvious improvement
introduced by Mamedyarov. Obtaining the bishop pair is more significant than
the weakening of the kingside.} (12. a4 a6 13. e4 (13. g4 Bg6 14. Nh4 $1 $14)
13... Qb6 14. Qe3 c5 $132 {, and Black had strong counterplay in Batsiashvili,
N -Brunello, M Riga LAT 2017.}) 12... Bg6 13. Nh4 Qb6 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. a4 Rac8
{Mamedyarov,S -Gozzoli,Y chess.com INT 2019} ({I think better chances for
equality are given by the more natural} 15... a6 16. Nf3 Rac8 17. axb5 axb5 18.
g5 $1 Nh5 (18... Nd5 $6 19. e4 Nc7 20. Be3 $14) 19. Bd2 c5 20. dxc5 Nxc5 21.
Qe3 Na4 22. Qxb6 Nxb6 23. b3 Nd5 24. e3 b4 25. Ra7 $14 {White has an advantage
in the endgame as Black's knight is arrested on h5.}) 16. axb5 $1 {Adding a
central pawn majority to the bishop pair advantage is an improvement over the
game continuation.} (16. Nf3 a5 17. Rd1 Rfd8 18. g5 Nd5 19. e4 Nb4 20. Be3 Qa6
$14) 16... cxb5 (16... g5) 17. g5 $1 {An important detail to White's plan.} Ne8
(17... Nh5 18. Ne4 $1 $36) 18. Nf3 (18. Qa2 $5 Qxd4 19. Nf3 Qd6 20. Qxa7 $14) (
18. Ne4 $5 $14) 18... a5 19. Qd3 a4 20. Bd2 Nd6 21. b3 $14 {I prefer White
here, but the position remains very dynamic.} *

