{[%evp 0,44,30,30,14,-16,34,34,34,-33,-32,-32,20,0,-1,-30,-35,-35,-3,-13,-4,
-20,-2,-2,-11,28,31,-21,40,-6,19,5,-2,5,0,-11,7,-30,-53,-89,-86,-93,-59,-59,
-59,-38,-28]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qb3 dxc4 5. Qxc4 Bg4 6. Nbd2 Nbd7
7. g3 e6 8. Bg2 Be7 9. O-O O-O {[%eval 402,0]} 10. b3 {is White's most natural
option. Black has many possible plans here, but he must hurry to create
concrete counterplay by c6-c5, as otherwise he risks falling under pressure
once White completes the bind with Bb2, Rac1, Rfd1.} Rc8 $1 {I like this
concrete approach .Black is ready to play b5 followed by c5.} (10... Qa5 {
Black is connecting the rooks, hoping to achieve Qh5, a nice location near the
White king. In this line very instructive are the games Bu Xiangzhi - Wang Rui
China 2015 - and Miroshnichenko-Korneev from Khanty 2005 (model game section).}
11. h3 $1 {may be more precise.} (11. Bb2 Qh5 (11... Rac8 12. h3 Bh5 13. Rfc1
c5 (13... Bg6 14. e3 Ne4 15. Qe2 Nxd2 16. Nxd2 Qc7 17. a3 Qb8 18. h4 h6 19. b4
Bd6 20. Nc4 Bc7 21. a4 $36 {Palac,M -Loiacono,L Spilimbergo ITA 2019}) 14. e3
Nb6 15. Qc3 $1 {This endgame is well-known to be in White's favour, as his Bg2
is much stronger than the Bh5.} (15. Qf1 $5) 15... Qxc3 16. Bxc3 Nbd5 17. Bb2
Rc7 (17... Nb4 18. Ne5) (17... Nd7 18. Nc4 b6 19. g4 Bg6 20. Nfe5 $14) 18. dxc5
Rfc8 19. Ne5 Rxc5 20. Kf1 $1 {would keep the advantage for White.} (20. a3 Be2
$1 {Braun,A -Vogel,R Boeblingen GER 2016})) 12. Rfe1 Bh3 13. e4 Rac8 14. Rac1
$14 {preserved a slight advantage for White in Zhou Weiqi -Bai,J Xinghua CHN
2016.}) 11... Bh5 $1 (11... Bf5 $6 {is well-known to be inferior due to} 12.
Nh4 $1 (12. Bb2 Ne4 $5 {Bu Xiangzhi -Wang Rui China CHN 2015}) 12... Nb6 (12...
b5 $5 13. Qxc6 Rac8 14. Nxf5 $1) 13. Nxf5 Nxc4 (13... Qxf5 14. Qc3 Nbd5 15. Qb2
$14 {[%cal Ge2e4]}) 14. Nxe7+ Kh8 15. Nxc4 $16 {Miroshnichenko,E-Korneev,O
Khanty-Mansiysk 2005}) 12. Bb2 Rfd8 13. e3 $1 $14 (13. Rfc1 Ba3 $1 $11) 13...
Ba3 14. Qc1 Bxb2 15. Qxb2 $14) (10... Bf5 11. e3 (11. Bb2 h6 (11... Ne4 $5 {
Ionov,S -Soffer,R Hersonissos GRE 2017}) 12. Rad1 Ne4 13. Qc1 Qa5 14. a3 (14.
Nh4 Nxd2 15. Nxf5 exf5 16. Rxd2 Nf6 17. e3) 14... Qb5 {, and now Ivanchuk
missed the moment for the typical} 15. d5 $3 (15. Rfe1 $11 {Ivanchuk,V -Navara,
D Huai'an CHN 2016}) 15... cxd5 16. Nd4 Qa6 17. Nxf5 exf5 18. Nxe4 fxe4 19.
Rxd5 Nf6 20. Bxf6 (20. Rd4 $14) 20... Bxf6 21. e3 Rfc8 22. Qb1 Qxa3 23. Rd7 $16
) 11... Ne4 12. Bb2 h6 13. Qe2 Bh7 14. Nc4 $14 {Ramirez,A -Miranda Mesa,E
Merida MEX 2014}) (10... a5 {With the inclusion of a5 a3, Black hopes to make
use of the hole on b3.} 11. a3 (11. Bb2 $6 a4 $1 $36) 11... h6 $5 (11... Rc8
12. Bb2 b5 13. Qc2 c5 14. Rfc1 cxd4 (14... Nb6 $6 15. Ne5 Bxe2 16. Ne4 Bh5 17.
Nxf6+ (17. dxc5 $16 {Parvanyan,A -Ragger,A Karlsruhe GER 2019}) 17... Bxf6 18.
dxc5 $16) 15. Qxc8 Qxc8 16. Rxc8 Rxc8 17. Nxd4 e5 (17... Nd5 18. h3 Bh5 19. g4
Bg6 20. Bxd5 exd5 21. Nxb5 Rc2 22. Bc3 $16 Bd8 23. Nf3 Rxe2 24. Nfd4 Re4 25. b4
) 18. Nc6 Bd6 19. Rc1 Nb6 20. e3 $16 {Fish,G -Sandipan,C Solingen GER 2015}) (
11... Qb8 $5 12. Bb2 b5 13. Qc2 Rc8 14. Rac1 h6 (14... Bf5 15. e4 Bg6 16. Nh4)
15. Rfe1 Bf5 16. e4 Bh7 17. Qb1 c5 $132) 12. Bb2 Bf5 13. Rfd1 (13. e3 $5) 13...
Bh7 (13... Qc7 14. Ne5 Rfd8 15. e4 Bh7 16. Nd3) 14. Ne5 $1 (14. e3 Qb6 15. Ne5
$14 (15. Rac1 Rfd8 16. Ne1 $14)) 14... Qc7 15. Nxd7 Nxd7 16. e4 $14 {With the
exchange of a pair of knights, White cut off the Bh7, reaching the ideal
position for this line.}) 11. Bb2 {There is no way to prevent Black's idea.} (
11. h3 Bh5 12. Bb2 b5 13. Qc2 Bg6 14. Qd1 c5 $11 {Fridman,D -Laznicka,V
Solingen GER 2014}) (11. e3 b5 12. Qd3 Qb6 13. Bb2 c5 {Khalifman,A -Can,I St
Petersburg RUS 2019}) 11... b5 12. Qc2 c5 $1 13. Rfc1 $1 ({After} 13. Rac1 Qb6
$1 {Black's queen finds a nice stay on a6 from where it both attacks the a2
pawn, defends the c8 rook and supports c5-c4.} 14. Rfe1 (14. Qb1 Qa6 15. h3 (
15. dxc5 Nxc5 $11) 15... Bh5 16. Qa1 c4 $1 {Schneider Zinner,H -Schachinger,M
St Johann im Pongau AUT 2016}) 14... Qa6 15. Qd3 (15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Qb1 Bf5)
15... Qxa2 16. Bc3 c4 $36 {, and Black took over the initiative and soon won
in Huang Qian -Goryachkina, A Qinhuangdao CHN 2018.}) 13... Nd5 ({More natural
and safe is} 13... Qb6 $5 14. a4 a6 15. axb5 axb5 16. Qd3 Rfd8 17. e3 Bf5 (
17... Nd5 18. Qf1) 18. Qe2 Bg6 19. Bf1 b4 {, and Black is very close to
equality in Van der Werf, M -Kuipers, S Wijk aan Zee 2018.}) ({The immediate} 
13... cxd4 $6 14. Qxc8 Qxc8 15. Rxc8 Rxc8 16. Nxd4 a6 17. h3 Bh5 18. Bb7 $1 $16
{gave White a big advantage in Handke, F -Kuipers, S Caleta ENG 2016.}) 14. Qd1
Qb6 15. dxc5 Nxc5 (15... Bxc5 16. Ne4 Be7 17. Qd4 Qxd4 18. Nxd4 a6 19. Nc6 $1
$16) 16. Bd4 ({Taking the bishop pair with} 16. Ne5 Bh5 17. g4 Bg6 18. Bd4 Rfd8
19. Nxg6 hxg6 {is not an improvement, as after} 20. e3 Qb8 21. Nf3 Nb4 $132 {
Black has enough counterplay.} 22. Qe2 a6 23. Ne5 Bd6 $1) 16... Rfd8 (16... Bf6
$11) 17. Qc2 Qb8 ({The immediate} 17... f6 $1 {is even more precise, with the
idea} 18. Ne4 Bxf3 19. Bxf3 Nxb3 $1 $15 20. Qxc8 $2 Nxd4 $1 $19) 18. Qb2 f6 19.
Nf1 e5 (19... Qd6 {Predke,A -Inarkiev, E Izhevsk RUS 2019}) 20. Ne3 Be6 21.
Nxd5 Bxd5 22. Be3 a5 $11 *

