{[%evp 0,51,30,30,13,-9,39,34,36,18,10,-32,36,-6,11,-35,-35,-23,-4,-4,3,4,6,
-16,-13,-9,-11,0,5,0,4,8,4,-4,12,-7,0,7,0,13,18,8,6,3,18,4,86,117,118,104,91,
111,167,167]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 dxc4 5. Qxc4 Bg4 6. Nbd2 e6
7. g3 Nbd7 8. Bg2 Be7 9. O-O O-O {[%eval 402,0]} 10. Ne5 {The idea behind this
natural move is to exchange a pair of knights followed by e2-e4, excluding
Black's bishop from play. The inventor of this idea is the great hungarian GM
Layos Portish. Nowadays it is a prefered choice by many outstanding
theoreticians like Harikrishna, Ivanchuk, Vitiugov, Bologan, Vaganian and many
other strong players.} Bh5 (10... Nb6 $5 11. Qd3 Bh5 12. Ndf3 Nfd7 13. g4 $14)
(10... Nxe5 $2 11. dxe5 $18) (10... Bf5 $6 11. e4 Bg6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. Qe2 $14
) 11. Nxd7 (11. Ndf3 $5 {Is a solid alternative.} Qb6 $5 ({In the game
Portisch,L-Barczay, L Budapest 1964 Black pushed too early} 11... c5 $6 {
, and after} 12. Nxd7 (12. Rd1 $5 $14) 12... Nxd7 13. dxc5 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Ne5
15. Qe4 Nxf3+ 16. Qxf3 Bxc5 17. Qxb7 {White won a pawn, but Black was able to
make a draw.}) 12. Be3 (12. b3 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Rfd8 14. Bb2 Nd7 15. Nxd7 Rxd7 16.
a4 a5 17. e3 Qd8 (17... Qb4 18. Ba3 Qxc4 19. bxc4 Bxa3 20. Rxa3) 18. Rfc1 $14 {
White can continue practically without any risk.}) 12... Rad8 13. g4 $5 {
could be very unpleasant, for example} Nxg4 14. Nxg4 Bxg4 15. d5 $1 Qb4 16.
Qxb4 Bxb4 17. dxc6 bxc6 18. Bxa7 $5 $146 ({An improvement over} 18. Nd4 {
Shabalov,A -Lintchevski,D Jurmala LAT 2016}) 18... Bxf3 19. Bxf3 Ne5 20. Bg2
Rd2 21. e3 Nc4 22. a3 Be7 23. a4 $1 {, and White has a dangerous passed pawn
supported by a strong bishop pair.}) (11. h3 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 (12... Nd5 $1
13. g4 Bg6 14. Ne4 Qb6 15. Kh2 Bxe4 16. Bxe4 f6) 13. g4 Bg6 14. f4 Nb6 15. Qb3
Qd4+ 16. e3 Qd3 17. e4 Qxb3 18. Nxb3 f6 $132 {Sjodahl,P -Gozzoli,Y Erts AND
2014}) 11... Nxd7 $1 ({After} 11... Qxd7 {White successfully implemented his
plan.} 12. Nb3 $1 Rfd8 (12... Rad8 13. e4 Bg6 14. f3 Ne8 15. Bf4 $14 {Bates,R
-Gourlay,I Hinckley Island ENG 2015}) 13. e4 $1 Rac8 (13... a5 14. a4 b5 15.
Qc2 bxa4 $5 (15... Bg6 16. Be3 (16. axb5 $1 a4 17. Nc5 Bxc5 18. bxc6 Qxc6 19.
Qxc5 Qb7 20. f3 $14) 16... Nd5 17. Rfc1 $6 Nb4 (17... Nxe3 18. fxe3 e5 $1 $15)
18. Qe2 bxa4 19. Nc5 Qc7 20. Nxa4 $16 {, and White got a significant advantage
in Le,Q -Gelfand,B Astana 2012.}) 16. Rxa4 c5 17. Rc4 cxd4 18. Nxd4 $14 {
Oganian,M -Zhurikhin,A Sochi RUS 2018}) 14. Be3 $6 (14. f3 $1) 14... Bg6 $6 (
14... Ng4 $1) 15. f3 Qe8 16. Rfd1 Nd7 {Oganian,M -Dreev,A St Petersburg RUS
2018, and now White could have played} 17. Na5 $1 $36 {, creating strong
pressure on the queenside.}) 12. Nb3 (12. Nf3 $143 Rc8 13. Rd1 Bxf3 14. Bxf3
Ne5 $11) 12... a5 ({Worth investigating is} 12... Rc8 $5 {, again having in
mind the typical idea b5 followed by c5.} 13. Bd2 $1 (13. e4 c5 $1 $132 {
Oganian,M -Kozionov,K Samara RUS 2015}) (13. Rd1 $5) 13... b5 (13... Nb6 $142
$5) 14. Qd3 Qb6 15. Ba5 Qb8 16. Rac1 c5 17. Nxc5 Nxc5 18. dxc5 Bxc5 19. b4 $5
$14 (19. e3 $11 {Harikrishna,P -Le,Q Ha Long City 2009})) 13. a4 (13. Bf4 Nb6 (
13... a4 14. Nc5 Nxc5 15. dxc5 Qa5 16. Rac1 Rfd8 $11 {Levin,F -Chabanon,J
Hockenheim GER 2015}) 14. Qc2 Nd5 $36) 13... Bb4 {The other moves do not
change much.} (13... Qb6 14. e4 Rfd8 15. Be3 Qb4 16. Rfc1 $5 (16. Qc2 e5 $11 {
