e4 Nc7 20. Bf4 $44) 16... bxc6 17. Nxc6 Qd6 18. e4 Nfd5 19. Bd2 Rfc8 20. exd5
Nxd5 $11) 10... Be7 (10... Qxb3 11. Nxb3 {gives White an important tempo to
create pressure - already the threat is Na5. But it is Black's last chance to
exchange queens.} Be4 (11... a5 12. Ne5 a4 (12... Nbd5 13. Bd2 $1 Bb4 {Kengis,
E -Zapolskis,A Liepaja 2004} 14. Bxb4 axb4 15. Rfc1 $16) 13. Nc5 Bxc5 14. dxc5
Nbd7 15. Nc4 $1 {Elizarov,D -Frolov,A Taganrog 2011} Nxc5 16. Be3 Nfd7 17. Rac1
$44) 12. Na5 O-O-O 13. Ne5 Bxg2 (13... Bg6 14. a3 Rxd4 15. b4 $44) 14. Kxg2
Rxd4 15. Nxf7 Rg8 {, and in Zherebukh,Y-Ma,Q Fujairah 2012 White is better due
to his greater piece activity and better pawn structure.} 16. Nb3 Rd5 17. Ng5
$14) 11. Qd1 $1 (11. a4 $5 {is an interesting alternative. In the game Fridman,
D-Akopian,V Porto Carras 2011 White had the initiative after} Qxb3 12. Nxb3 a5
13. Ne5 (13. Bd2 $1 Nc4 14. Be1 $36) 13... Bc2 14. Nc5 Bxc5 15. dxc5 Nbd7 16.
Nxd7 Nxd7 17. Bd2 Ke7 18. Rfc1 $14 {, but it appeared very difficult for White
to make any progress.}) (11. e3 $5 Qxb3 12. Nxb3 Be4 (12... a5 13. Ne5 $1) 13.
Na5 Rb8 14. Bd2 O-O 15. Rfc1 Rfc8 16. Ne5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Kf8 {Ponomariov,R
-Akopian,V / Astrakhan 2010} 18. f3 $14) 11... O-O 12. e3 $1 {Black got the
mainline with two extra moves: Qd5 and Nb6. But they are both not well placed
