Ne8 20. Bb4 $11 {Black is very close to equality and managed to hold the
endgame.}) 9... O-O 10. Rd1 {We arrived at the main position of the line with
dc4 & Bf5. Black has 4 main continuations: 10...Qb6, 10 ... e5, 10...Rc8 and
10...Qc7.} Qb6 $1 {Defending the knight on d7 to be able to answer Nc3 with
Ne4. The other moves are weaker:} (10... Qa5 {is not that popular for some
reason. I think that White can try} 11. Bd2 Qb6 12. b4 Ne4 13. Be1 Rfd8 {
Gundavaa,B- Solak,D Aeroflot open 2012, and now either} 14. Nc3 ({or} 14. a4
$14 {should give White somewhat better play.})) 11. Qe2 {White is ready to
execute his plan of mobilising his central pawn majority with Nc3, e4, Be3.
Black should look for a convincing way to meet it. The counterplay with c6-c5
is not so effective here, and I think that Black's best chance is to look for
simplifications with a timely Ne4.} Rfd8 $1 {Defending the knight on d7 to be
able to answer Nc3 with Ne4. The other moves are weaker:} (11... c5 {is not
the right approach, as after} 12. Nc3 $1 $14 {it appears that Black is only
helping White in achieving his goal.} Ne4 {is a tactical error when the knight
on d7 is undefended.} (12... Rfd8 $6 13. e4 $1 Bg4 14. Be3 $14) (12... cxd4 13.
Nxd4 Bg4 (13... Bg6 14. e4 $14) 14. f3 Bh5 15. e4 $1 {Wojtkiewicz,A -Zatonskih,
A San Diego 2004} e5 16. Na4 Qa5 17. Nf5 Bb4 18. b3 Rfd8 19. a3 Bf8 20. Bd2 Qc7
21. Rac1 $16) 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Ne5 $1 Bxg2 15. Nxd7 Qc6 16. Ne5 Qd5 {Jojua,D
-Sibashvili,G Tbilisi 2016 , and White missed the refutation} 17. f3 $1 $146
cxd4 18. f4 $3 Bh3 19. Rxd4 Qa5 20. Bd2 Qa6 21. Qxa6 bxa6 22. Rc1 $16 {Black's
bishop is out of play and White enjoys a big advantage in the endgame.}) (11...
Rad8 12. Nc3 Ne4 {is almost the same as the mainline.}) (11... Qb5 $5 {The
only game where this original move was played is Wojtkiewicz, A-Qureshi, A
FIDE.com 2001. Offering the queens' exchange spoiling the pawn structure may
be strategically risky, but in the game, Black managed to keep the balance and
even outplayed his higher-rated opponent.} 12. Qxb5 (12. Qe1 $5) 12... cxb5 13.
Ne1 Be4 14. Nc3 (14. f3 Bc6 15. e4 $14) 14... Bxg2 15. Kxg2 b4 16. Ne2 Rac8 17.
Bd2 a5 18. f3 Nb6 19. b3 Nbd5 20. Rac1 $14 Nc7 21. e4 h6 22. Rc4 Nb5 23. Rdc1
$14 {White should be better in this endgame.} ({More precise was} 23. Rxc8 $1
