{[%evp 0,45,30,30,15,-10,45,36,36,18,18,-24,-15,-31,-23,-22,-18,-18,-18,-23,
-18,-43,-32,-26,7,-9,10,-11,26,4,36,17,26,38,35,32,40,38,52,40,43,27,27,21,44,
44,45,38]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 dxc4 5. Qxc4 Bf5 6. g3 e6 7. Bg2
Nbd7 8. O-O Be7 9. e3 O-O 10. Rd1 e5 {[%eval 503,0] This move was played for
the first time in the game Mamedyarov - Aronian 2010 Tal Memorial . Black is
in a hurry to challenge White's central supremacy, using the moment when the
rook d1 is undefended. But as we will see it doesnt bring him any positive
results.} 11. Nc3 $1 {When Black is attacking the centre, this knight always
stands better on c3.} (11. dxe5 $6 Nxe5 12. Rxd8 Nxc4 13. Rxa8 Rxa8 14. Nd4 Bg6
$11) 11... Qc7 12. e4 $1 {This surprising idea was introduced by Navara
against Bruzon in 2011 and in some sense is refuting the concept behind 10...
e5.} ({After} 12. h3 Rfe8 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 15. e4 Be6 16. Qe2 {
Black is very close to equality, although the statistics show that White is
dominating +3 =1.}) 12... Bg4 ({In the game Batsiashvili,N -Osmak,I
Khanty-Mansiysk 2017 Black accepted the pawn sacrifice and White got a furious
compensation for it:} 12... Nxe4 13. Nd5 Qd8 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7 15. dxe5 $1 Nxe5 (
15... Rad8 16. Bf4 Nb6 17. Qe2 Nd5 18. Nd4 $1 $18) 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. Bf4 Qe6
18. Qb4 b5 19. Re1 $1 a5 20. Qd4 Rad8 (20... c5 21. Qe3 Rfe8 22. g4 Bg6 23. h4
h6 24. h5 Bh7 25. f3 Nf6 26. Qxc5 $16) 21. Qb6 Qg6 22. Rac1 Rc8 23. Qxa5 $16 {
White's bishops are too strong.}) (12... Be6 13. Qe2 $14) 13. Be3 exd4 (13...
Rad8 14. Rac1) 14. Bxd4 Bxf3 (14... Bd6 $6 {is refuted by the surprising} 15.
Bxf6 $1 gxf6 (15... Nxf6 16. Rxd6 Bxf3 17. Nb5 Qe7 18. Bxf3 cxb5 19. Qd4 $16)
16. h3 Ne5 17. Qe2 Nxf3+ 18. Bxf3 Bxh3 19. Bg4 Bxg4 20. Qxg4+ Kh8 21. Qf5 Qe7 (
21... Be5 $6 22. Kg2) 22. Kg2 $44 {, with great compensation.}) 15. Bxf3 Ne5
16. Qe2 Nxf3+ 17. Qxf3 Rad8 18. Rac1 $14 Qa5 19. Rc2 $1 $146 {is a very strong
novelty. White is preparing to double the rooks on the open file and at the
same time sets a nasty trap.} (19. Kg2 Rfe8 20. Rc2 h6 21. Rcd2 $14) (19. a3 {
Three games arrived at this position: Navara, D-Bruzon Batista, L Havana 2011
Borovikov, V-Baghdasaryan, V Chennai 2013 Donchenko, A -Hacker, J Warsaw POL
2016, and in two of them White won before move 40. Despite the exchange of two
pairs of minor pieces, White is firmly holding the initiative - his goal is to
either achieve e4-e5 at a favourable moment or to take control over the open
file. Black's only counterplay is to exchange the strong bishop on d4 by
Nd7-Bf6.} Nd7 $1 (19... Rfe8 20. Kg2 h6 21. h4 a6 22. Rc2 Nh7 (22... Nd7 $2 23.
Bxg7 $1) 23. e5 Nf8 24. Ne4 Ne6 25. Bc3 Qa4 26. Rcd2 Rxd2 27. Rxd2 c5 28. b3
Qxb3 29. Rb2 Qxa3 30. Rxb7 Nd4 31. Qg4 Qa4 32. Rxe7 Rxe7 33. Nf6+ $18 {Navara,
D -Bruzon Batista,L Havana 2011}) 20. Kg2 (20. Bxg7 $2 {does not work here:}
Kxg7 21. Rxd7 Rxd7 22. Qg4+ Qg5 {, as the c1 rook is hanging.}) 20... Bf6 21.
