{[%evp 0,29,23,20,27,27,32,-16,38,-3,12,-19,-2,14,11,2,32,-11,30,9,30,26,26,44,
64,23,14,23,15,27,22,22]} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 c6 4. Qb3 {The main reason
to investigate 4.Qb3 is that having two options on move 4 will let you be more
flexible and will increase the surprise effect. Of course, the difference
between 4.Qc2 and 4. Qb3 matters only when Black declines to take on c4. If I
have to compare the two options, I can suggest the following rule of thumb:
When your opponent usually responds to 4.Qc2 with g6, then 4.Qb3 should be
more unpleasant to meet, as 4.Qb3 g6 5.Nc3 Bg7 6.cxd5! is in White's favour.
And if the opponent generally prefers the classical 4...e6, then I think 4.Qc2
is the right approach, because in QGD structures, with a queen on c2 White
preserves better chances to obtain an advantage compared to the lines with a
queen on b3.} e6 {[%eval 101,0] Now White has to make a choice between the
Catalan with Qb3 - 5.g3 and the Classical Queen's Gambit Declined with the
queen on b3 - 5.Bg5} 5. Bg5 Nbd7 (5... dxc4 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qc2 Bb7 {leads to
chapter 6 - line 6.1.}) ({The attempt at a direct counterattack by} 5... h6 $5
6. Bh4 Qa5+ (6... g5 7. Bg3 Ne4 8. Nc3 Nxg3 9. hxg3 Bg7 10. O-O-O) 7. Nc3 Ne4 {
is not entirely correct, for example} 8. e3 Nd7 9. Bd3 g5 10. Bg3 Nxg3 (10...
h5 11. Bxe4 dxe4 12. Ne5 h4 13. Nxd7 Kxd7 14. Be5 $16) 11. hxg3 Bg7 12. O-O-O
dxc4 13. Bxc4 Nb6 14. Kb1 Nd5 15. Ne4 $16 {led to a huge initiative for White
in Epishin, V-Burmakin, V Bugibba 2011}) (5... Qa5+ $6 6. Bd2 $1 Qb6 7. Qc2 {
is in White's favour, for example} Ne4 (7... c5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. e4 (9. dxc5)
9... Nb4 10. Bxb4 Qxb4+ 11. Nbd2 Nc6 12. d5 Nd4 13. Nxd4 cxd4 14. a3 Qa5 15.
Qb3 $16) 8. e3 Nxd2 9. Nbxd2 Nd7 10. Bd3 Be7 11. O-O h6 12. Rfe1 O-O 13. Rac1
$14) (5... a5 $5 {is a very interesting and fresh idea. Recently, this became
Black's standard weapon for creating counterplay in all types of positions
with the queen on b3 - we will see it again in line 1.1.2.} 6. Nbd2 ({Black's
main point is that} 6. Nc3 {is not good for White after} a4 $1 7. Nxa4 dxc4 $36
) 6... a4 (6... h6 7. Bh4 a4 8. Qc2 dxc4 9. Qxc4 a3 10. b3 Nbd7 11. e3 Qa5 12.
Bd3 Nd5 13. Qc1 Nb4 14. Be2 b5 15. O-O $14 {was insufficient for equality in
Magalashvili,D -Grachev,B / Yerevan 2006}) 7. Qc2 a3 8. b3 Na6 $5 {, and Black
has good counterplay.} (8... Bb4 9. e3 h6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Bd3 O-O 12. O-O Nd7
13. Rac1 $14) 9. e3 Nb4 10. Qc3 Qa5 11. Bxf6 {The only move.} (11. Be2 $6 Ne4
$19) 11... gxf6 12. Be2 e5 13. dxe5 (13. O-O Bg7 $132) 13... Bf5 14. O-O Nc2
15. Qxa5 Rxa5 {, and White has nothing better than} 16. Rad1 Nb4 17. Nd4 Bd7
18. exf6 Nxa2 19. Ra1 Nb4 20. Rfc1 {, preserving dynamic equality in the
