Bxc4 O-O 13. e5) 12. Nd2 Bxd4 13. exd5 Nc5 14. Qc2 cxd5 15. cxd5 exd5 16. Kb1
$16) 7. e3 O-O {We have arrived at the starting position of the QGD with the
queen on b3. Compared to the QGD with the queen on c2, it has not been as
extensively played and analyzed, therefore White's main continuation is not
yet established. White can choose between the following four moves: A) 8 Rd1,
B) 8 Rc1, C) 8.Bd3, and D) 8.Be2. The most natural plan for Black against each
of these options is to solve the problem of the development of the
light-squared bishop by b6-Bb7 - with or without the inclusion of h6 Bh4 -
followed by c6-c5. The only problem arises in the B) 8.Rc1 line, when White
achieves better chances with the precise 9.cxd5! The other bullet-proof plan
is the classical simplifying manouevre dxc4&Nd5, followed by taking on c3 and
e6-e5. But when White recaptures on c4 with the queen, Black must change plans
and push c5! The extended fianchetto with dxc4 and b5 is also playable and
leads to dynamic play. The most dangerous idea is to build the battery on the
b1-h7 diagonal. Black always has the clever option of inserting the move a7-a6
to gain a tempo if White plays Bd3 and then has to play Bd3xc4. After some
investigation I made the conclusion that line D) offers the best chances.} (
7... a6 8. cxd5 $1 Nxd5 (8... cxd5 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O $14) 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Bd3
