8. Be2 dxc4 9. Bxc4 b5 10. Be2 Be6 11. Qc2 b4 12. Qa4 Qb6 $36) 8... Nbd7 9. Be2
{, and here Black can exploit the white queen's position on b3 by playing} (9.
h3 e5 $1 10. dxe5 Ne4 $132) 9... Nh5 $1 10. Bxh5 dxc4 $1 11. Qd1 (11. Nxc4 Qxh5
12. O-O e5 $11) 11... Qxh5 12. Qxh5 gxh5 13. Nxc4 b6 14. Ne4 Ba6 15. Rc1 Rac8
16. b3 c5 $11 {, with comfortable equality.}) (5. g3 Bg7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O {
transposes to the symmetrical Gruenfeld fianchetto system.}) 5... Bg7 (5...
dxc4 6. Qxc4 Bg7 7. Bf4 {transposes to Chapter 2 - 2.1} (7. e4 {might be even
better.} O-O 8. Be2 {Transposing to the Russian Variation with 5. Qb3 in the
Gruenfeld Defence, where I do not think that 6...c6 is Black's best reply, for
example:} b5 9. Qb3 Qa5 10. e5 $1 Be6 11. Qc2 Nd5 12. O-O $14)) 6. cxd5 $1 cxd5
(6... Nxd5 $5 {is a playable option that rapidly gained in popularity after
the recent top game Vidit - Artemiev Poikovski-Karpov 2018. The game continued}
7. e4 Nxc3 8. bxc3 O-O 9. Be3 (9. Ba3 $5 Nd7 10. Be2 c5 11. O-O b6 12. Rad1 $14
) 9... c5 {, and now best would have been:} 10. Be2 $5 {For example:} ({
Instead of the more principled:} 10. d5 Nd7 11. Bd3 $6 b5 $36) 10... cxd4 11.
cxd4 Nc6 12. Rd1 Qa5+ 13. Rd2 Bg4 14. O-O $14) 7. Bg5 Nc6 8. e3 e6 ({In this
move order,} 8... Na5 {is not good anymore} 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Qa4 Nc6 11. Ne5 $1
$14) (8... O-O $6 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qxd5 {Black does not have enough for the
pawn:} e5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. d5 Nb4 13. O-O-O e4 14. Nxe4 Nxa2+ 15. Kb1 Bf5 16.
Bd3 Bxe4 17. Bxe4 Nb4 18. Rd2 $16 (18. d6 Rd7 19. Rd2 $16)) 9. Bd3 {In this
symmetrical pawn structure, White has a pleasant long-term advantage because
of his better piece activity. (Compare the bishops Bg5 / Bg7 and Bd3 / Bc8).
Furthermore, White is usually the first to take control of the open c-file.}
O-O (9... h6 10. Bf4 g5 11. Bg3 Nh5 12. Be5 $1) 10. h3 $1 {A very strong
prophylactic move, which enables White to preserve the important g5-bishop.} (
10. O-O h6 11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 Nh5 $11) 10... Na5 (10... Qb6 $6 {leads to a
very unpleasant endgame. Black lost both games after a long and painful
defence.} 11. Qxb6 axb6 12. Ke2 Bd7 (12... Nb4 13. Bb5 Nc6 14. Bf4 Bd7 15. Bc7
Na7 16. Bd3 b5 17. a3 Rfc8 18. Bb6 {Gurevich,M -Malich,B Germany 1992}) 13. a3
Rfc8 14. Rhc1 Na5 15. Nd2 {David,A -Skembris,S /Paleochora 2011}) (10... Qa5
11. O-O Qb4 12. Qc2 ({The endgame is also pleasant for White.} 12. Qxb4 Nxb4
13. Bb5 $14 {Lenderman,A -Friesen,V /Bad Wiessee 2014}) 12... a6 13. Rfc1 Bd7
14. a3 Qe7 15. Na4 Rac8 16. Nc5 $14 {White exerts very annoying pressure on
Black's queenside.}) (10... b6 11. Ne5 $1 Bb7 12. O-O h6 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. Bf4
Ne4 15. Rfc1 $16) 11. Qc2 Bd7 (11... b6 12. O-O Bb7 13. Ne5 $14) 12. Ne5 $1 Rc8
13. Qe2 {We are following the highly instructive game Tkachiev, V -Berend, E /
Nancy 2015.} h6 14. Bh4 a6 15. O-O Nc6 16. f4 Be8 17. Ng4 $1 (17. Rac1 $14)
17... h5 18. Ne5 Qb6 19. Rac1 Nb4 $2 {A desperate attempt to create
counterplay, but it is met with a tactical refutation.} 20. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 21.
Nxd5 $18 *

