1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Bg5 dxc4 5. Qa4+ c6 6. Qxc4 Qb6 $6 {This is
the most principled - attacking the b2 pawn is a clever way to punish White
for his early bishop move.} 7. Nbd2 $1 {If White defends the pawn, Black will
take over the initiative.} (7. Qc2 c5 (7... Nbd7 8. e3 c5 $11) 8. e3 Nc6 $11) (
7. Qc1 c5 8. Nbd2 Nc6 9. Nc4 Qd8 10. dxc5 Bxc5) 7... Qxb2 8. Rb1 Qa3 9. e4 b6 (
9... Nbd7 {Black protects the knight on f6, not allowing the destruction of
his pawn structure on the kingside.} 10. Bd3 {Now Black has a certain problem
with the development of the kingside.} h6 $1 {An improvement over 10... Nb6.
Black's idea is simple - he wants to complete the development of the kingside.}
({The only earlier game saw} 10... Nb6 11. Qc2 Bb4 12. Rb3 Qa5 13. O-O h6 14.
Bxf6 gxf6 15. Nc4 Nxc4 16. Bxc4 Bd6 17. d5 $16 {1-0 Khenkin, I-Ramirez Alvarez,
A/Moscow 2004/EXT 2005 (52). (51)}) ({For example after} 10... Be7 {White can
either exchange the dark-squared bishop immediately by means of} 11. e5 ({
or play} 11. Qc2 {[%cal Gd2c4]} Qa5 12. O-O {, keeping the idea of e5 for
better times.}) 11... Nd5 12. Bxe7 {[%csl Rd6] , creating a weakness on d6.}
Qxe7 13. Ne4 N7b6 14. Qc1 O-O 15. O-O Rd8 16. Qd2 Bd7 17. Rfc1 Be8 18. Nc5 Rab8
19. Rb3 f5 20. exf6 Qxf6 21. Be4) 11. Bf4 ({In case of} 11. Bh4 Nh5 {[%csl Rd3,
Rg2][%cal Gh5f4] would be strong.}) 11... Be7 (11... g5 12. Bc7) (11... Qa5 $5
12. O-O) (11... Nh5 12. Be3) 12. Qc2 {[%cal Gd2c4] White creates the threat
Nc4.} (12. Bc7 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gc4c2] was interesting, taking away the
a5-square from the black queen.} O-O (12... c5) 13. Qc2 {[%cal Gd2c4]}) 12...
Qa5 {Black runs away with the queen.} 13. O-O O-O {Black has succeeded in
developing his kingside and bringing the queen back, but his position remains
passive, although reliable.} 14. Nb3 {Huzman places his knight on b3 to
control the important advance c6-c5.} ({Nevertheless} 14. Nc4 {was worth
trying, as the knight is more active on c4 and has the option to jump to d6.}
Qd8 15. Rfd1 b6) 14... Qd8 {[%cal Gf6h5] It's understandable that Black wants
to keep the queen safe, but it was possible to disturb White by means of} (
14... Qa4) 15. h3 $1 {A useful move. White wants to preserve the bishop on the
b8-h2 diagonal.} Re8 16. Rfd1 Bf8 {Black is lacking active ideas, but his
position is tough to break.} 17. Bh2 a5 {Black urgently needs some fresh air.}
18. Nbd2 a4 19. Nc4 $44 {For the pawn White has long term pressure. Huzman, A
-Kogan,A /Montreal 2005}) 10. Qc2 Ba6 11. Bc4 $1 $146 {A very strong novelty.}
Bxc4 12. Nxc4 Qa6 13. O-O $1 {Sacrificing a second pawn.} Nxe4 $8 {There is no
way back.} (13... Be7 14. e5 $16) (13... Nbd7 14. Nce5 Rc8 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16.
Nxc6 $16) 14. Qxe4 Qxc4 15. Rbc1 $1 Qa4 (15... Qd5 16. Qxd5 exd5 17. Rfe1+ Kd7
18. Ne5+ Kc7 19. Nxf7 Rg8 20. Re8 $18) 16. Ne5 {White has a winning initiative
- all his pieces are ready to launch the final attack.} Bd6 (16... Ba3 17. Rc3
$1 (17. Rc4 Qb5 18. Qf3 O-O 19. Qxa3 f6) (17. Nxf7 Kxf7 18. Rc3 Be7 $1 19. Re1
Qxa2) 17... O-O 18. Rh3 g6 19. Rxh7 $18) 17. Nc4 (17. Nxc6 O-O 18. Nd8 $18)
17... Bc7 18. d5 $3 {A beautiful discovered attack.} O-O $8 (18... cxd5 $4 19.
Nd6+ $18) 19. dxe6 $18 Na6 $2 (19... fxe6 20. Rc3 $1 (20. Qxe6+ Kh8 21. Be7 Re8
22. Rc3 Na6 $17) 20... Nd7 21. Rh3 Nf6 22. Bxf6 Rxf6 23. Qxh7+ Kf7 24. Rd3 $1
Re8 25. Rd7+ Re7 26. Rxe7+ Kxe7 27. Qxg7+ Rf7 $16) 20. Be7 f5 (20... Nc5 21.
Bxc5 bxc5 22. e7 Rfe8 23. Rfe1 $16) 21. Qd3 Rfe8 22. Qd7 Kh8 23. Rc3 $18 (23.
Bd6 Red8 24. Qe7) 23... b5 24. Bf6 $1 Rg8 25. Ne5 Bxe5 26. Bxe5 Qe4 27. f4 $1
Nc5 28. Qd6 Nb7 29. Qe7 {This game like the previous one is a perfect tool for
learning to develop the initiative in the opening. Logically after this
convincing defeat, there were no more followers in taking the pawn on b2.} 1-0

