1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 dxc4 5. Qxc4 Bf5 6. g3 e6 7. Bg2 Be7 8. O-O
Nbd7 9. e3 O-O 10. Rd1 Qc7 11. Nc3 $1 {After the game this became established
as White's best continuation.} e5 (11... Nd5 $1 {is more solid and gives Black
more chances for equality.}) 12. e4 $1 $146 {A bolt from the blue. Elegant and
strong, easy when you see it. Touch of the genie! This move brings new life
into the variation, as the previously played} (12. Qe2 e4 13. Nh4 Bg4 14. f3
exf3 15. Bxf3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 c5 $132 {is quite fine for Black}) 12... Bg4 13.
Be3 $14 (13. d5 Nb6) 13... exd4 14. Bxd4 Bxf3 {Black opts for simplifications.}
(14... Rfe8 $1) 15. Bxf3 Ne5 16. Qe2 Nxf3+ 17. Qxf3 Rad8 18. Rac1 Qa5 19. a3 (
19. Rc2 $1 {prevents Black's Nd7 & Bf6 idea.} Nd7 20. Bxg7 $1) 19... Rfe8 (
19... Nd7 20. Kg2 Bf6 21. Bxf6 Nxf6 $14) 20. Kg2 h6 (20... Nd7 $1 21. Bxg7 $2
Kxg7 22. Rxd7 Rxd7 23. Qg4+ Bg5 24. Qxd7 Bxc1 25. Qxe8 Bxb2 $17) 21. h4 $1 a6 (
21... Nd7 22. Bxg7 Kxg7 23. Rxd7 Rxd7 24. Qg4+) 22. Rc2 Nh7 {Black opts for
passive defence.} (22... Nd7 23. Bxg7) (22... h5 $5 23. Qf4 Ng4 24. f3 Bf6 25.
Bxf6 Nxf6 26. Rcd2 Rxd2+ 27. Qxd2 (27. Rxd2 Rd8) 27... Re7 28. Qd6 Qe5 29. Qxe5
Rxe5 30. Na4 $14) 23. e5 Nf8 24. Ne4 Ne6 25. Bc3 $14 Qa4 26. Rcd2 Rxd2 27. Rxd2
c5 28. b3 (28. Nd6 Bxd6 29. exd6 Qd7 $16) 28... Qxb3 (28... Qc6 29. Nd6 Rb8)
29. Rb2 Qxa3 (29... Qc4 30. Nd2) 30. Rxb7 Nd4 31. Qg4 Qa4 $2 32. Rxe7 Rxe7 33.
Nf6+ {Black was really in very bad shape in this game. The surprising novelty
promised White only a slight edge but after passive play and a final mistake
by Black it was just too easy for White.} 1-0

