1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 dxc4 5. Qxc4 (5. e4 b5 6. b3) 5... Bg4 6.
Nc3 Nbd7 7. e4 Bxf3 (7... e5 $1 {This move became Black's main weapon only
after a game played next year at the Olympiad 2014 in Tromso.}) 8. gxf3 e5 $1
9. dxe5 ({RR} 9. Be3 exd4 {is the mainline according to my analysis - see
chapter 3.} (9... Bd6 10. O-O-O exd4 11. Bxd4 Qc7 12. Ne2 O-O 13. Qc2 b5 14.
Kb1 Rfe8 15. Bh3 c5 16. Be3 Nb6 17. Bg5 Be5 18. Bc1 Nh5 19. Rhg1 Nc4 20. b3
Rab8 21. Rg5 g6 22. Rdg1 Kh8 23. f4 Bf6 {Ponomariov,R (2739)-Gelfand,B (2758)/
Khanty Mansiysk 2009/CBM 134/1-0 (34)})) 9... Nxe5 10. Qe2 {White's queen goes
back and Black should be on alert, as f3-f4 is a big threat.} Bc5 $1 ({Both} 
10... b5) ({and} 10... Bb4 {are significantly worse.}) 11. Bd2 (11. f4 $4 Nfg4
$19) 11... Nh5 $5 {This was a novelty at that time. The point of this move is
revealed only after the following unexpected sacrifice. After other moves
White exerts strong pressure.} (11... b5 12. O-O-O Qb6 13. f4 Nc4 14. Qf3 {
is good for White.}) (11... Qe7 12. f4 Ned7 (12... Neg4 13. e5 Nxf2 14. exf6
Qxe2+ 15. Kxe2 Nxh1 16. fxg7 Rg8 17. Ne4 Bd4 18. Nd6+ Kd7 19. Nf5 Bxg7 20. Nxg7
Rxg7 21. Bh3+ $18) 13. e5 $16) 12. f4 Qxd2+ $3 {The only way to justify the
previous move.} 13. Kxd2 (13. Qxd2 $4 Nf3+) 13... Nxf4 {Black has only knight
and pawn for the queen, but the control over the dark squares and the
centralised position of White's king give Black a strong initiative.} 14. Qd1 {
This ugly retreat is the only move.} (14. Qe1 $4 Nf3+) 14... O-O-O+ 15. Nd5 {
White is forced to give back some part of his extra material.} Nxd5 {'!'} ({
It later proved to be better to take with the pawn.} 15... cxd5 $1 {The
following lines are extraordinary - Black's knights are dominating the board.}
16. Kc2 $1 (16. Qb3 dxe4+ 17. Kc1 Kb8 18. Qg3 Bd6 $19) (16. Qc1 Kb8 17. Qxc5
dxe4+ 18. Ke3 Nd5+ 19. Kd4 (19. Kxe4 $2 Rhe8) 19... Nf6+ 20. Ke3 (20. Kxe5 Nd7+
21. Kd4 Nxc5+ 22. Kxc5 Rd2 23. b3 Rc8+ 24. Kb4 Rxf2 25. Bc4 f5 $44) 20... Nd5+
21. Kd4 Nf6+ 22. Ke3 $11) 16... Kb8 $1 17. Qd2 Rc8 18. Kb3 (18. Kb1 g5 19. exd5
Rhd8 20. a3 Rxd5 21. Qc2 Bd4 22. Qb3 Rd6 23. a4 Ne6) 18... Ne6 19. Qxd5 Bd4 $1
20. Qd6+ (20. f4 Nf3 21. Rd1 Bb6 22. Qh5 (22. a3) 22... Nfd4+ $17) 20... Ka8
21. Rd1 Rhd8 22. Qa3 Rc6) 16. Kc1 $2 {Over the board it is close to impossible
to find the most precise move. The position is crazy and there is huge tension
on the d-file so naturally White moves his king away.} (16. Qb3 Nb4+ 17. Kc1
$13 {, and Black still has to prove his compensation.} Nbd3+ 18. Bxd3 Rxd3 19.
Qc2 Rf3 20. Kb1 Rxf2 21. Qc3 Re8 22. Rd1 b6 23. a3 $14) 16... Nf4 (16... Ne3
17. Bh3+ Kb8 18. Qh5 Nd3+ 19. Kb1 Nc4 20. a3 g6 21. Qg5 Bd4 {is probably
stronger}) 17. Qc2 Bxf2 {Collecting a second pawn.} 18. Kb1 Bb6 (18... Bd4) 19.
a3 {[%cal Gb1a2]} Rd6 20. Ka2 Rhd8 $32 21. Rb1 g5 (21... Kb8) 22. Qb3 Rd2 23.
Bh3+ Kc7 {At this point Black should not have any trouble maintaining equality,
his knights are too strong.} 24. Bf5 h5 $6 {Releasing the pressure. From this
point, White had some winning chances, which he missed in his huge time
trouble.} (24... Nfd3 $5 $36) 25. Rbd1 R8d3 26. Rxd2 Rxb3 (26... Rxd2 27. Qc3
Rd4 28. Rf1 h4 29. Rd1 Nfd3 30. Bh3 f6 {Black builds some kind of fortress.})
27. Kxb3 Be3 28. Rdd1 g4 29. Rhe1 Bc5 (29... Bf2 30. Rf1 Be3 31. Rde1 Bd2 $11)
30. Rf1 Ng2 (30... Be3 $11) 31. Rd2 Nh4 (31... Ne3 32. Rh1 h4) 32. Rfd1 Nhf3
33. Rd8 $16 h4 34. Rh8 (34. Rg8) (34. Ka4) 34... h3 $1 {[%csl Rh2,Gh3]} 35. Rh1
(35. Rg8) (35. Rc8+ Kb6 36. Rg8 Nxh2 37. Rh1 Nhf3 38. Bxg4 $16) 35... Be3 36.
Rg8 Bg5 37. Rd1 Kb6 38. Kc3 Bf6 39. Kb3 (39. Kc2 Bg5 40. b4 a5) 39... Bg5 40.
Kc3 Bf6 41. Kb3 1/2-1/2

