{This game is one of the most amazing I have ever seen! It significantly
increased the popularity of the 4.Qc2 system and served as a model game for
the development of the initiative in the opening.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6
4. Qb3 e6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 dxc4 7. Qxc4 b5 8. Qc2 Bb7 9. Nbd2 $5 Nbd7 10. e4 $1
{The only way to fight for an advantage.} Rc8 {[%emt 0:00:06] After Black was
quickly crushed in this game, Rc8 logically disappeared from chess practice.
Better is Qb6 or a6 - see Chapter 6.} 11. Be2 (11. a4 Bb4 {is too slow.}) 11...
a6 (11... c5 12. d5 $1 {is very strong as well.} exd5 13. e5 g5 14. Bg3 Ne4 15.
Nxe4 dxe4 16. O-O-O $18) 12. O-O c5 {Having said A Black also says B. Rc8 only
makes sense with a quick c5.} (12... Qb6 13. Rad1 c5 14. d5 $1 $36) (12... Be7
$6 13. e5 Nd5 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Ne4 $16) 13. d5 $1 exd5 {The following lines
clearly demonstrate White's attacking potential.} (13... Bd6 14. dxe6 fxe6 15.
Rfd1 Qb6 16. Bxf6 (16. e5) 16... gxf6 17. e5 $1 fxe5 18. Qg6+ Kd8 19. Ne4 $16)
(13... Qb6 14. Rfe1 exd5 15. Bd3 $16) 14. e5 g5 {The fact that Black finds it
necessary to use such extreme measures does not bode well for his defence.} 15.
Bg3 Ne4 (15... Nh5 $2 16. e6 $18) 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Nd2 (17. e6 fxe6 18. Ne5
$18) 17... h5 $2 {A very bad idea, but Black has no defence anyway.} (17... Qe7
18. Nxe4 Nxe5 19. Bg4 $3 Nxg4 (19... Rd8 20. Bxe5 Qxe5 21. Nxc5 $18) 20. Rfe1
$16) (17... Bg7 18. Nxe4 Bxe5 19. Rad1 Bxg3 20. Rxd7 $1 Kxd7 (20... Qxd7 21.
Nf6+ $18) 21. Rd1+ Kc7 22. Rxd8 $18) 18. Nxe4 Rh6 (18... Bxe4 19. Qxe4 h4 20.
e6 Nf6 (20... hxg3 21. exd7+ Kxd7 22. Rad1+ $18) 21. Qb7 fxe6 22. Be5 $18) (
18... h4 19. e6 $1 fxe6 20. Nd6+ Bxd6 21. Qg6+ Ke7 22. Qg7+ $18) 19. Rad1 Be7 (
19... h4 20. Bg4 hxg3 21. fxg3 Rc7 22. Nf6+ Rxf6 (22... Ke7 23. Qd2 $18) 23.
exf6 Qa8 24. Rfe1+ Kd8 25. Qe2 $18) 20. Bxh5 $1 {Mamedyarov is one of the
strongest tacticians in the chess world elite. In this position, with Black
desperately defending, his beautiful final combination serves as a way to
shorten terrible suffering.} Rxh5 (20... Bc6 21. Bg4 c4 22. Rfe1 Kf8 23. Nf6
$18) (20... Bxe4 21. Qxe4 Rxh5 22. e6 $18) 21. e6 {Players above 2700 rarely
win direct duels in 20 moves!} (21. e6 fxe6 (21... Bc6 22. exd7+ Bxd7 23. Rd5
Qa5 24. Rxd7 Kxd7 25. Qd1+ Kc6 26. Qxh5 $18) 22. Nd6+ Kf8 23. Qg6 $18) 1-0

