1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qc2 dxc4 5. Qxc4 Bg4 6. Nbd2 Nbd7 7. g3 e6 8.
Bg2 Be7 9. Ne5 {The exchange of knights is a step forward in the plan of
encaging the bishop with e4, f3, but it doesn't change the evaluation of this
equal position.} Bh5 10. Nxd7 (10. Ndf3 {Without the inclusion of 0-0 0-0 this
move makes no sense because of} Qa5+ 11. Bd2 Qd5 $11) 10... Nxd7 (10... Qxd7 $6
11. Nb3 O-O 12. O-O $14) 11. O-O O-O 12. Nb3 {The knight has no better square,
but its invasion on c5 is not really a threat.} (12. Ne4 Qb6) (12. e3 e5 $1)
12... a5 $1 {[%cal Ra5a4] A typical motif when a knight is on b3.} (12... Bd6
13. e4 Qe7 14. Be3 $14) (12... Qb6 13. e4 a5 14. Be3 a4 15. Nd2 Qa5 16. a3 e5
$11) 13. a4 {Weakening b4, but there is no choice.} (13. e4 a4 14. Nc5 Nxc5 15.
dxc5 Bf6 16. Bf4 Qd4 17. Qxd4 Bxd4 18. Bd6 Rfd8 19. Rab1 e5 $15) 13... Bb4 {
[%csl Gb4] Immediately exploiting the new outpost on b4. Black had many other
moves, some of them quite sufficient for equality:} (13... Nb6) (13... e5 $5
14. Qc2 Bg6 15. e4 exd4 16. Nxd4 Ne5 $1 17. Rd1 Bh5 $132) 14. e4 e5 $1 $146 {
A new but quite obvious continuation.} (14... Qe7 15. Be3 Rfd8 16. f4 Kh8 17.
Rf2 f6 18. Bd2 e5 {Ivanchuk,V -Vallejo Pons,F Istanbul 2012 was also good for
Black. In all these games e6-e5 is an important resource, so Anand decide to
play it immediately.}) 15. Be3 exd4 16. Bxd4 Kh8 $1 {Black is planning to
bring his h5-bishop into play by means of ...f7-f6 and ...Nh5-f7.} 17. e5 $6 {
Too aggressive.} (17. f4 f6 18. Bf2 $11) 17... Re8 18. f4 f6 $1 19. exf6 Nxf6
$15 {White's centre has been destroyed, and the weakness of the light squares
remains.} 20. Bf3 Bxf3 21. Rxf3 Re4 (21... c5 $5 22. Be5 $140 Ng4) 22. Re3 $6 (
22. Qd3 $142 Qe8 23. Re3 $15) 22... Rxe3 23. Bxe3 Qe8 24. Bb6 $6 (24. Bd4 Rd8
$1 $17 {[%cal Ge8e1,Gd8d1]} (24... Qe4 $143 25. Nc5)) 24... Qh5 25. Bd4 {
White has simply lost a tempo, and Black quickly activates his forces.} Re8 {
[%cal Re8e2]} 26. Rf1 $6 (26. Be5 Qf3 $17) 26... Ng4 27. Qc2 c5 $1 {A deadly
blow.} 28. Nxc5 (28. Bxc5 Bxc5+ 29. Nxc5 Ne3 $19) 28... Rc8 {[%cal Rb7b6,Rb4c5,
Gc8c2] The pin is decisive.} 29. Rd1 Bxc5 30. Bxc5 h6 31. Kh1 {I think after
this game White's plan with 9 Ne5 & 10 Nd7 lost most of its supporters.} 0-1

