1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qb3 dxc4 5. Qxc4 Bg4 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. Bf4 $1 {
Only a couple of weeks after the Carlsen game from Tromso Olympiad, Mamedyarov
is moving a step forward. Black has no easy life anymore and needs to adjust
his plans.} Nb6 8. Qd3 Nbd5 $1 {Starting immediate action before White can
take control of the centre.} 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 (9... Nxd5 10. Bd2) 10. Ne5 $1 (10.
Nd2 $5 Bf5 11. Qc3 {with the idea f3&e4.}) 10... Rd8 (10... Be6 11. f3 Rd8 12.
e4 Qxd4 13. Qxd4 Rxd4 14. Be3 Rd6 15. Bxa7 Nd7 {, and only} 16. Nc4 $1 {
gives hope for something more than a draw.}) 11. e3 $1 ({Of course not} 11.
Nxg4 $6 Nxg4 12. e3 e5 $36) 11... e6 12. f3 $1 Bb4+ 13. Kf2 Bf5 14. Qb3 $1 {
There was no need to complicate:} (14. e4 $5 Bxe4 15. fxe4 Nxe4+ 16. Kg1 Qxd4+
17. Qxd4 Rxd4 18. Be3 $14 {, and although a piece should be worth more than
Black's pawns, the realisation is not at all simple.}) 14... Qxb3 15. axb3 a6 (
15... Nd5 16. Bg3 f6 17. Nc4 Bc2 18. Rxa7 b5 19. Na5 Bxa5 20. Rxa5 Bxb3 21. Ra6
$18) 16. Bxa6 $1 {Torpedo style.} (16. e4 Bg6 17. Bxa6) 16... bxa6 17. Nxc6 a5
18. Nxd8 Kxd8 19. e4 Bxe4 (19... Bg6 20. Rhc1 Ne8 21. Rc6 Ke7 22. Rac1 f6 23.
Ra6 Bf7 24. Bc7 $18) 20. fxe4 Nxe4+ 21. Kf3 Nf6 22. Be5 Ne8 23. Rhc1 $18 (23.
d5 exd5 24. Rhd1) 23... Kd7 24. Rc4 f6 25. Bg3 h5 26. h4 Rh6 27. Be1 Bxe1 28.
Rxe1 Nd6 29. Rc5 Nb7 30. Rc3 Rg6 31. Rec1 Kd6 32. Rc7 Nd8 33. Rc8 Nf7 34. R8c6+
Kd5 35. R1c4 Rg4 36. Rc7 Nh6 37. Rd7# {Quite an easy game - with his logical
novelty, Mamedyarov won practically without a fight.} 1-0

